ef name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''c''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_c}} Revised and expanded version of Ravaisson's 1834 prize winning essay ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref>\n* '''d''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_d}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-6\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 6</ref>\n* '''e''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_e}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''f''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_f}} See Sinclair ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n'''General: Primary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Sinclair, Mark'''. ''Being Inclined: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson\u2019s Philosophy of Habit'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2019)\n{{refend}}\n\n\n'''General: Secondary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Carlisle, Clare'''. \"Between Freedom and Necessity: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson on Habit and the Moral Life\", in ''Inquiry'' (43/2: 2010), pp. 123\u201345\n*'''Carlisle, Clare and Mark Sinclair'''. \"Editors\u2019 Introduction\" and \"Editors\u2019 Commentary\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Of Habit'', translation, introduction, and commentary by Clare Carlisle and Mark Sinclair (London/New York: Continuum, 2008), pp. 1-21; 78-114 \n*'''Grosz, Elizabeth'''. \"Habit Today: Ravaisson, Bergson, Deleuze and Us\", in ''Body and Society'' (19/2\u20133: 2013), pp. 217\u201339\n*'''Sinclair, Mark'''. \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays'', edited by Mark Sinclair; translated by Jeremy Dunham, Adi Efal, Mark Sinclair, Tullio Viola (London: Bloomsbury, 2016), pp. 1-29\n{{refend}}\n\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ravaisson-Mollien, Felix}}\n[[Category:1813 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:French archaeologists]]\n[[Category:French philosophers]]\n[[Category:People from Namur (city)]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n[[Category:Aristotelian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox philosopher\n|region           = [[Western philosophy]]\n|era              = [[19th-century philosophy]]\n|image            = Felix_Ravaisson-Mollien.jpg\n|name             = Felix Ravaisson-Mollien\n|birth_date       = 23 October 1813\n|birth_place      = [[Namur, Belgium|Namur]], [[First French Empire|France]]\n|death_date       = {{d-da|18 May 1900|23 October 1813}}\n|death_place      = [[Paris]], [[French Third Republic|France]]\n|education        = [[Coll\u00e8ge-lyc\u00e9e Jacques-Decour|Coll\u00e8ge Rollin]]\n|alma_mater       = [[University of Munich]]\n|institutions     = [[University of Rennes]]\n|school_tradition = [[Continental philosophy]]<br>[[French spiritualism]]\n|main_interests   = [[Metaphysics]]<br>[[:de:Positive Philosophie|Positive philosophy]]\n|notable_ideas    = Criticism of French [[Eclectic philosophy|eclecticism]]\n|influences       = [[Aristotle]], [[Ren\u00e9 Descartes|Descartes]], [[Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz|Leibniz]], [[Blaise Pascal|Pascal]], [[Maine de Biran]], [[Victor Cousin]], [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling|Schelling]]\n|influenced       = [[Henri Bergson]], [[Louis Lavelle]], [[Martin Heidegger]], [[Maurice Merleau-Ponty]], [[Pierre Hadot]], [[Dominique Janicaud]], [[Paul Ric\u0153ur]], [[Fran\u00e7ois Laruelle]]\n}}\n'''Jean-Gaspard-F\u00e9lix Lach\u00e9 Ravaisson-Mollien''' ({{IPA-fr|\u0281av\u025bs\u0254\u0303 m\u0254lj\u025b\u0303|lang}}; 23 October 1813 &ndash; 18 May 1900) was a French philosopher, 'perhaps France\u2019s most influential philosopher in the second half of the nineteenth century'.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-1\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 1</ref> He was originally and remains more commonly known as '''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson'''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-1\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 1</ref> His 'seminal' 'key' work was ''De l\u2019habitude'' (1838), translated in English as ''Of Habit''.<ref name=\"CarlisleBFN-125\">\"Carlisle (2010), p. 125</ref><ref name=\"SinclairI-1\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. 1</ref><ref name=\"GroszHT-219\">\"Grosz (2013), p. 219</ref> Ravaisson's philosophy is in the tradition of [[Spiritualism_(philosophy)|French Spiritualism]], which was initiated by [[Maine de Biran|Pierre Maine de Biran]] (1766 \u2013 1824) with the essay \"The Influence of Habit on the Faculty of Thinking\" (1802). However, Ravaisson developed his doctrine as what he called \u2018spiritualist realism\u2019 and \u2018spiritualist positivism\u2019, and - according to Ravaisson scholar [[Mark Sinclair (philosopher)|Mark Sinclair]] - can be thought of as founding 'the school of contingency'.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-9-10\">\"Sinclair (2019), pp. 9-10</ref> His most well known and influential successor was [[Henri Bergson]], with whom the tradition can be seen to end during the 1930s;<ref name=\"SinclairBI-1\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 1</ref> although the 'lineage' of this 'philosophy of life' can be seen to return in the late twentieth century with [[Gilles Deleuze]].<ref name=\"GroszHT-219\">\"Grosz (2013), p. 219</ref> Ravaisson never worked in the French state university system, in his late 20s declining a position at the University of Rennes.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref> In 1838 he was employed as the principle private secretary to the Minister of Public Instruction, going on to secure high-ranking positions such as Inspector General of Libraries, and then the Curator of Classical Antiquities at the [[Louvre]].<ref name=\"SinclairBI-8\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 8</ref> Later in his life he was appointed as the President of the Jury of the Aggregation of philosophy in France, 'a position of considerable influence'.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-9\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 9</ref> Ravaisson, was not only a philosopher, classicist, archivist, and educational administrator, but also a painter exhibiting under the name Lach\u00e9.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-8\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 8</ref> \n\n==Biography==\n\n[[File:Th\u00e9odore Chass\u00e9riau - Portrait of Jean-Gaspard-F\u00e9lix Larcher Ravaisson-Mollien.JPG|thumb|left|alt=A portrait of F\u00e9lix Ravaisson by Th\u00e9odore Chass\u00e9riau.|F\u00e9lix Ravaisson by Th\u00e9odore Chass\u00e9riau (1846)]]\n\nRavaisson was born at [[Namur]]. After a successful course of study at the [[Coll\u00e8ge-lyc\u00e9e Jacques-Decour|Coll\u00e8ge Rollin]], he went to [[University of Munich|Munich]] in autumn 1839, where he attended the lectures of [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph Schelling|Schelling]], and took his degree in philosophy in 1836. In the following year he published the first volume of his famous work ''Essai sur la m\u00e9taphysique d'Aristote'' (\"Essay on the Metaphysics of Aristotle\"), to which in 1846 he added a supplementary volume. This work not only criticizes and comments on the theories of [[Aristotle]] and the [[Peripatetic school|Peripatetic]]s, but also develops from them a modern philosophical system.\n\nIn 1838 he received his doctorate, his thesis entitled \"De l'habitude\" (\"On Habit\"), which was to become a classic text (a metaphysical 'poem' on nature in general apprehended through an intuitive analysis of acquired habit as a particular manifestation of its essential being, much admired by Bergson and Heidegger), and became professor of philosophy at [[Rennes]]. From 1840 he was inspector-general of public libraries, and in 1860 became inspector-general in the department of higher education. He was also a member of the [[Acad\u00e9mie des Sciences Morales et Politiques|Academy of Moral and Political Sciences]], and curator of the Department of Antiquities at the [[Louvre]] (from 1870). He died in [[Paris]].\n\nIn philosophy, he was one of the school of [[Victor Cousin]], with whom he was at issue in many important points. The act of consciousness, according to him, is the basis of all knowledge. Acts of consciousness are manifestations of will, which is the motive and creative power of the intellectual life. The idea of God is a cumulative intuition given by all the various faculties of the mind, in its observation of harmony in nature and in man. This theory had considerable influence on speculative philosophy in France during the later years of the 19th century.\n\n==Bibliography==\n\nRavaisson\u2019s 'complete' 'three major' philosophical works are: ''Essai sur la m\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' [Vol. 1 & Vol. 2] (1837 and 1846); ''De l\u2019habitude'' (''On Habit'', 1838); and ''Rapport sur la philosophie en France au XIXeme si\u00e8cle'' (1867).<ref name=\"SinclairBI-6\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 6</ref><ref name=\"Carlisle&Sinclair-4-5\">\"Carlisle & Sinclair (2008), pp. 4-5</ref> Ravaisson also produced a number of other 'noteworthy essays' such as \"La Philosophie contemporaine\" (\"Contemporary Philosophy\", 1840); \"La Philosophie de Pascale\" (\"Pascal\u2019s Philosophy\", 1887), and \"M\u00e9taphysique et Morale\" (\"Metaphysics and Morals\", 1893).<ref name=\"Carlisle&Sinclair-5\">\"Carlisle & Sinclair (2008), p. 5</ref> Upon his death he also 'left unfinished fragments of a major work, which were published posthumously', first as \"Testament philosophique\" in ''Revue de m\u00e9taphysique et de morale'' (\"Philosophical Testament\", 1901), then later in extended form as ''Testament philosophique'' (''Philosophical Testament'', 1933).<ref name=\"Carlisle&Sinclair-5\">\"Carlisle & Sinclair (2008), p. 5</ref><ref name=\"SinclairI-vii\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vii</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"border:none\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Original Publication Details\n! English Title\n! English Publication Details\n|-\n\n| 1834\n| ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote''\n| Originally unpublished competition manuscript.{{ref label|Rav_Bib_a|a|}}<br/>Selections in ''De la nature \u00e0 l\u2019esprit'' (2001).{{ref label|Rav_Bib_b|b|}}\n|\n|\n|-\n\n| 1837\n| ''Essai sur la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' [Vol. 1]{{ref label|Rav_Bib_c|c|}}\n| Paris: Imprimerie Royale, 1837.{{ref label|Rav_Bib_d|d|}}\n|\n|\n|-\n\n| 1838\n| ''De l\u2019habitude''\n|  Sorbonne doctoral thesis (primary).{{ref label|Rav_Bib_e|e|}}<br/>Paris: H. Fournier, 1838.{{ref label|Rav_Bib_f|f|}}\n| ''Of Habit''\n| F\u00e9lix Ravaisson, ''Of Habit''<br/>London & New York: Continuum, 2008<br/>Trans., intro., & commentary by Clare Carlisle & Mark Sinclair\n|-\n\n| 1838\n| ''Speusippi de Primis Rerum Principiis Placita Qualia Fuisse Videantur ex Aristotele''\n| Sorbonne doctoral thesis (secondary; in Latin)\n| \n| \n|-\n\n| 1840\n| \"La Philosophie contemporaine: Fragments de philosophie par M. Hamilton\"\n| in La Revue des deux mondes, 1840, pp.397\u2013427\n| \"Contemporary Philosophy\"\n| Translated by J. Dunham in Ravaisson: Selected Essays, 59\u201384\n|-\n\n| 1845\n| ''Essai sur la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote''  [Volume 2]\n| Paris: Joubert, 1845\n|\n|\n|-\n\n| 1851 or 1856?\n| \"Rapport sur le stoicisme\"\n| \n| \"Essay on Stoicism\"\n| chapter 3 of Sinclair volume\n|-\n\n| 1853\n| \"Rapport address\u00e9 \u00e0 M. le ministre de l\u2019Instruction publique et des cultes\"\n| (28 December 1853); published in 1853 as De l\u2019enseignement du dessin dans les lyc\u00e9es (Paris: Dupont)\n| \"The Art of Drawing According to Leonardo da Vinci\" [Partial translation]\n| by Mark Sinclair in F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays, ed. M. Sinclair (London: Bloomsbury, 2016) 145\u201358\n|-\n\n| 1867\n| ''La Philosophie en France au XIX\u00e8me si\u00e8cle''\n| Paris: Hachette, 1889, 3rd edn [1867]\n| \n| \n|-\n\n| 1871\n| \"Venus de Milo\"\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n\n| 1873\n| \"Greek Funerary Monuments\"\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n\n| 1875\n| \"Les classiques de l'art: modles pour l'eenseignemnet du dessin\"\n| \n| \n| \n|-\n\n| 1882\n| \"On Teaching of Drawing\"\n| article in Ferdinand Buisson's Dictinnoary de pedagogie et\n| 'On Teaching of Drawing'\n| chapter 5 of Sinclair collection\n|-\n\n| 188?\n| \"Mysteries\"\n| \n| \"Mysteries\"\n| (chapter 8 in Sinclair) on Greek religion\n|-\n\n| 1887\n| \"La Philosophie de Pascale\"\n| La Revue des deux mondes 80 (1887) 399\u2013428\n| \"Pascal\u2019s Philosophy\"\n| translated by Mark Sinclair in Ravaisson, Selected Essays, 253\u201378\n|-\n\n| 1892\n| \"Venus de Milo\"\n| second extended version of Venus essay\n| \"Venus de Milo\"\n| the philosophical 3rd section in Chapter 6 of Sinclair book\n|-\n\n| 1893\n| \"M\u00e9taphysique et morale\"\n| Revue de m\u00e9taphysique et morale 1, 1893, 6\u201325\n| \"Metaphysics and Morals\"\n| translated by Mark Sinclair in Ravaisson, Selected Essays, 279\u201394.\n|-\n\n| 1901\n| \"Testament philosophique\"\n| first edited and published by Xavier L\u00e9on in Revue de m\u00e9taphysique et de morale 9/1 (1901) 1\u201331 from notes left after his death\n| \n| \n|-\n\n| 1933\n| ''Testament philosophique''\n| expanded version by Charles Devivaise \n| ''Philosophical Testament''\n| translated by J. Dunham and M. Sinclair in Ravaisson, Selected Essays, 295\u2013336\n|-\n\n| colspan=\"5\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:10pt;\"| Notes<br />\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* '''a''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_a}} Sinclair in ''Being Inclined'': 'In 1834' when 21 years of age, Ravaisson 'was the remarkably young laureate of a competition organized by the ''Acad\u00e9mie des sciences morales et politiques'' on Aristotle\u2019s ''Metaphysics'' and its historical reception, with a dissertation - ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' - that he would later publish in a revised and expanded form as ''Essai sur la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' [Volume 1] (1837).<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref> See also Sinclair 'Introduction' in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-2-3\">\"Sinclair (2016), pp. 2-3</ref>\n* '''b''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_a}} Sinclair in ''Being Inclined'': 'Long sections of' ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote'' 'with the original pagination in the margins, are published in R. Belay and C. Marin, ''De la nature \u00e0 l\u2019esprit'' (Paris: ENS Editions, 2001), 201\u201313.'<ref name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''c''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_c}} Revised and expanded version of Ravaisson's 1834 prize winning essay ''De la M\u00e9taphysique d\u2019Aristote''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-7\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 7</ref>\n* '''d''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_d}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-6\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. 6</ref>\n* '''e''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_e}} See Sinclair in ''Being Inclined''.<ref name=\"SinclairBI-xi\">\"Sinclair (2019), p. xi</ref>\n* '''f''' {{Note|Rav_Bib_f}} See Sinclair ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays''.<ref name=\"SinclairI-vi\">\"Sinclair (2016), p. vi</ref>\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n'''General: Primary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Sinclair, Mark'''. ''Being Inclined: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson\u2019s Philosophy of Habit'' (Oxford: Oxford University Press, 2019)\n{{refend}}\n\n\n'''General: Secondary'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*'''Carlisle, Clare'''. \"Between Freedom and Necessity: F\u00e9lix Ravaisson on Habit and the Moral Life\", in ''Inquiry'' (43/2: 2010), pp. 123\u201345\n*'''Carlisle, Clare and Mark Sinclair'''. \"Editors\u2019 Introduction\" and \"Editors\u2019 Commentary\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Of Habit'', translation, introduction, and commentary by Clare Carlisle and Mark Sinclair (London/New York: Continuum, 2008), pp. 1-21; 78-114 \n*'''Grosz, Elizabeth'''. \"Habit Today: Ravaisson, Bergson, Deleuze and Us\", in ''Body and Society'' (19/2\u20133: 2013), pp. 217\u201339\n*'''Sinclair, Mark'''. \"Introduction\" in ''F\u00e9lix Ravaisson: Selected Essays'', edited by Mark Sinclair; translated by Jeremy Dunham, Adi Efal, Mark Sinclair, Tullio Viola (London: Bloomsbury, 2016), pp. 1-29\n{{refend}}\n\n\n'''Specific'''\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ravaisson-Mollien, Felix}}\n[[Category:1813 births]]\n[[Category:1900 deaths]]\n[[Category:French archaeologists]]\n[[Category:French philosophers]]\n[[Category:People from Namur (city)]]\n[[Category:French male writers]]\n[[Category:Aristotelian philosophers]]\n[[Category:Metaphysicians]]\n", "name_user": "McrPhilosophy", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBibliography:improving bibliography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F%C3%A9lix_Ravaisson-Mollien"}
{"title_page": "WWE 24/7 Championship", "text_new": "{{short description|American professional wrestling championship}}\n{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]] to this article about a current event, based on the nature of this subject, seems like it's likely to continue. This is the 7th protection log entry in just over two months.|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestling championship\n| name           = WWE 24/7 Championship\n| image          = WWE_24-7_Championship_belt.png\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = The WWE 24/7 Championship belt\n| currentholder  = [[Mojo Rawley]]\n| won            = March 25 or 26, 2020\n| aired          = April 4, 2020\n| created        = May 20, 2019\n| promotion      = [[WWE]]\n| brand          = <!--It's all the brands. We only need to put them here if it is specific to certain ones.-->\n| firstchamp     = [[Titus O'Neil]]\n| mostreigns     = [[R-Truth]] (35 reigns)\n| longestreign   = [[Riddick Moss]] (41 days){{efn|40 days as recognized by WWE.}}\n| shortestreign  = [[Mike Rome]] (9 seconds)\n| oldest         = [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]] ({{Age in years and days|January 19, 1941|July 22, 2019}}) \n| youngest       = [[Enes Kanter]] ({{Age in years and days|May 20, 1992|September 9, 2019}})                                     \n| heaviest       = [[The Revival (professional wrestling)| The Revival]] {{small|([[Scott Dawson (wrestler)|Scott Dawson]] and [[Dash Wilder]])}} ({{convert|446|lb|kg|abbr=on}} combined)\n| lightest       = [[Kelly Kelly]] ({{Convert|108|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}})\n| pastnames      = \n}}\n\nThe '''WWE 24/7 Championship''' is a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling championship#Weight class championships|championship]] created and promoted by the American [[professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] [[WWE]]. It is a tertiary championship open to anyone\u2014regardless of gender or WWE employment status\u2014and carries the special rule that it can be defended \"[[24/7]]\", as in any time, [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|anywhere]], as long as a WWE referee is present. Because of this rule, the championship is defended across all of WWE's brands\u2014[[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]], [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]], [[205 Live (WWE brand)|205 Live]], [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]], and [[NXT UK (WWE brand)|NXT UK]]\u2014as well as outside of regular shows, often with videos posted on the promotion's website and social media accounts. The current champion is [[Mojo Rawley]], who is in his seventh reign.\n\nThe title was unveiled by [[Mick Foley]] on the May 20, 2019 episode of ''[[Monday Night Raw]]'', where [[Titus O'Neil]] from Raw became the inaugural champion. It is similar to the previous [[WWE Hardcore Championship]], which also had a 24/7 rule. This rule can be temporarily suspended by an authority figure, usually done during a scheduled match for the title or matches that involve the champion.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Titus O'Neal 2017.jpg|thumb|upright|Inaugural 24/7 Champion [[Titus O'Neil]]]]\nDuring the [[Money in the Bank (2019)|2019 Money in the Bank]] pay-per-view on May 19, [[WWE]] announced that a new championship would be introduced on the following night's episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'',<ref name=\"MITB2019\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Money in the Bank results: Powell's live review of Seth Rollins vs. AJ Styles for the WWE Universal Championship, Kofi Kingston vs. Kevin Owens for the WWE Championship, Becky Lynch defends the Raw and Smackdown Women's Titles, two Money in the Bank ladder matches|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/05/19/wwe-money-in-the-bank-results-powells-live-review-of-seth-rollins-vs-aj-styles-for-the-wwe-universal-championship-kofi-kingston-vs-kevin-owens-for-the-wwe-championship-becky-lynch-defends-the-r/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=May 19, 2019|date=May 19, 2019}}</ref> where hardcore legend and [[WWE Hall of Fame]]r [[Mick Foley]] unveiled the WWE 24/7 Championship. Like the former [[WWE Hardcore Championship]] and its \"[[WWE Hardcore Championship#24/7 rule|24/7 rule]]\", the 24/7 Championship can be defended anytime, [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|anywhere]], as long as a WWE referee is present,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vgr.com/wwe-24-7-championship-belt-debuts-on-raw-now-available-in-wwe-2k19-downloads/|title=WWE 24/7 Championship Belt Debuts on Raw, Now Available in WWE 2K19 Downloads|last=Couden|first=Matt|date=May 21, 2019|website=VGR|language=en|access-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Johnson\" /><ref name=\"24/7belt\" /> hence its name. Due to this, Foley said the title can be defended on [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]], [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]], [[205 Live (WWE brand)|205 Live]], [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]], and [[NXT UK (WWE brand)|NXT UK]]. He also said that WWE legends could return and challenge for the title. After the unveiling, Foley laid the title belt in the ring and said that whoever secured the championship first in a scramble would become the inaugural champion. Raw's [[Titus O'Neil]] became the inaugural champion by doing so, defeating [[Cedric Alexander]], [[Drake Maverick]], [[Ethan Carter III|EC3]], [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]], [[Karl Anderson]], [[Luke Gallows]], [[Mojo Rawley]], and [[No Way Jose (wrestler)|No Way Jose]] to claim the championship.<ref name=\"Johnson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/126603/wwes-newest-championship-is.html?p=1|title=WWE'S NEWEST CHAMPIONSHIP IS...|last=Johnson|first=Mike|publisher=PWInsider|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"24/7belt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/new-24-7-title-unveiling-video/#.XONkdS2ZNQI|title=WATCH: Mick Foley Unveils New WWE 24/7 Title, First Champion Crowned|last=Satin|first=Ryan|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw05202019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/05/20/5-20-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-money-in-the-bank-fallout-will-brock-lesnar-announce-his-intensions-mick-foley-reveals-new-wwe-title/|title=5/20 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on Money in the Bank fallout, will Brock Lesnar announce his intensions, Mick Foley reveals new WWE Title|date=May 20, 2019|last=Keller|first=Wade|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> It was later confirmed that the title was not gender-exclusive and could also be won by non-WWE personnel after the respective wins of former female wrestler [[Kelly Kelly]] and [[Fox Sports|Fox]] sportscaster [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]].<ref name=\"Raw07222019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/07/22/7-22-wwe-raw-results-powells-review-raw-reunion-featuring-steve-austin-ric-flair-dx-hulk-hogan-and-many-more-alexa-bliss-talkshow-with-becky-lynch-the-build-to-summerslam-continues/|title=7/22 WWE Raw Results: Powell's review Raw Reunion featuring Steve Austin, Ric Flair, DX, Hulk Hogan, and many more, Alexa Bliss talkshow with Becky Lynch, the build to SummerSlam continues|date=July 22, 2019|last=Barnett|first=Jake|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FOX Founders Day\">{{cite web|last=Tedesco|first=Mike|title=WWE 24/7 Championship changes hands multiple times at FOX Founders Day event|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/136429-wwe-24-7-championship-changes-hands-multiple-times-at-fox-founders-day-event/|work=WrestleView|date=August 24, 2019|accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlthough a stipulation of the championship, the 24/7 rule can be temporarily suspended by an authority figure. This usually occurs when the champion is involved in a non-title match. For example, after [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]] won the title from [[R-Truth]] on the May 28, 2019 episode of ''[[SmackDown Live]]'', [[Shane McMahon]] suspended the rule until after the scheduled tag team match later that same night, in which both Elias and Truth were involved.<ref name=\"SmackDown05282019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/05/28/5-28-wwe-smackdown-live-results-barnetts-review-of-kofi-kingston-vs-kevin-owens-in-a-non-title-match-bayley-vs-lacey-evans-in-a-non-title-match-dolph-ziggler-on-the-kevin-owens-show/|title=5/28 WWE Smackdown Live Results: Barnett's review of Kofi Kingston vs. Kevin Owens in a non-title match, Bayley vs. Lacey Evans in a non-title match, Dolph Ziggler on the Kevin Owens Show|date=May 28, 2019|last=Barnett|first=Jake|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref> The rule can also be suspended during an actual scheduled match for the title to prevent other wrestlers from getting involved. For example, when R-Truth unsuccessfully defended the title against Elias in a [[lumberjack match]] on the June 4 episode of ''SmackDown''.<ref name=\"SmackDown06042019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/06/04/6-4-wwe-smackdown-live-results-barnetts-review-of-goldbergs-appearance-final-hype-for-wwe-super-showdown-in-saudi-arabia-bayley-on-a-moment-of-bliss/|title=6/4 WWE Smackdown Live Results: Barnett's review of Goldberg's appearance, final hype for WWE Super Showdown in Saudi Arabia, Bayley on A Moment of Bliss|date=June 4, 2019|last=Barnett|first=Jake|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref> Another example is when reigning champion R-Truth was a guest on [[The Miz]]'s \"Miz TV\" and during a subsequent scheduled match against Drake Maverick, both on the June 24 episode of ''Raw''.<ref name=\"Raw06242019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/06/24/6-24-wwe-raw-results-powells-review-of-u-s-champion-ricochet-vs-aj-styles-in-a-non-title-match-roman-reigns-vs-shane-mcmahon-and-drew-mcintyre-in-a-handicap-match-wwe-champion-kofi-kingston-vs/|title=6/24 WWE Raw Results: Powell's review of U.S. Champion Ricochet vs. AJ Styles in a non-title match, Roman Reigns vs. Shane McMahon and Drew McIntyre in a handicap match, WWE Champion Kofi Kingston vs. Sami Zayn in a non-title match|date=June 24, 2019|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[professional wrestling]] journalist [[Dave Meltzer]], the idea for the title was proposed by the [[USA Network]], where ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' had both aired (until ''SmackDown''{{'}}s move to [[FOX]] in October 2019), in an attempt to increase the ratings during ''Raw''{{'}}s third hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://solowrestling.mundodeportivo.com/new/80949-usa-network-ideo-el-campeonato-247-de-wwe|title=USA Network ide\u00f3 el Campeonato 24/7 de WWE|trans-title=USA Network devised the WWE 24/7 Championship|website=[[SoloWrestling]]|language=es|date=May 23, 2019|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The viewership of both shows had been declining; the April 29 and 30, 2019, episodes of ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'', respectively, both reached a record low for non-holiday broadcasts outside of football season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/05/03/wwes-viewership-is-tanking-fast-with-no-signs-of-slowing-down/#464a92927a3f|title=WWE's Viewership Is Tanking Fast With No Signs Of Slowing Down|date=May 3, 2019|last=Konuwa|first=Alfred|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> with viewership dropping off the most during ''Raw''{{'}}s third hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/129104-wwe-raw-ratings-viewers-down-again-april-29-third-hour-drop-sets-a-record-low/|title=WWE RAW Ratings: Viewers down again April 29, Third hour drop sets a record low|date=April 30, 2019|last=Tedesco|first=Mike|work=[[WrestleView]]|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2019, Meltzer reported that following the [[2019 WWE Draft]], the title would only appear on ''Raw'' as ''SmackDown'' was moving to FOX and the title was USA Network's idea. Although the title was established under the rule that it could be defended on any brand, it has primarily only appeared on ''Raw'' since that draft, though a couple of non-Raw wrestlers have won the title since then.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theringreport.com/wwe/backstage-news-on-the-24-7-championship-being-on-raw-and-wwe-keeping-couples-together-in-the-draft-a12286|title=Backstage News On The 24/7 Championship Being On RAW And WWE Keeping Couples Together In The Draft|date=October 15, 2019|last=Wilding|first=Josh|work=theringreport.com|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Belt design==\nThe championship belt design features three gold plates on a green leather strap. The circular center plate prominently states \"24/7\" at the center (\"24\" and \"7\" written in green). The WWE logo is affixed at the top while the word \"CHAMPION\" is written along the edge of the bottom half of the center plate. The two side plates, one on either side of the center plate, are rectangular. Unlike most of WWE's other championship belts, the side plates cannot be customized with the current champion's logos. They are mostly blank but with a simple ornate design on the bottom inner corner and top outer corner of each.<ref name=\"24/7belt\"/> As the belt lacks customizable side plates, Drake Maverick placed stickers that said \"Maverick 24:7\" in the blank space of the side plates,<ref>{{cite tweet|user=WWEMaverick|author=[[Drake Maverick]]|number=1146084264469049344|date=July 2, 2019|title=Side plates}}</ref> while [[Samir Singh]] placed stickers that spelled \"Bollywood\" around the center plate.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SinghBrosWWE|author=[[The Singh Brothers]]|number=1195381214678568961|date=November 15, 2019|title=Longest reigning 24/7 Champion in WWE history!}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=WWE|author=[[WWE]]|number=1196651601642962944|date=November 18, 2019|title=Ladies and gentlemen, your NEW 24/7 Champion... R-Truth! Watch how it all went down backstage! This night went from bad to worse for The Singh Brothers on RAW!}}</ref>\n\n== Reigns ==\n{{Main article|List of WWE 24/7 Champions}}\nAs of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTDAY}}, {{CURRENTYEAR}}, there have been 94 recognized reigns between 35 different people. [[R-Truth]] has the most reigns at 35 and the longest combined reign at {{age in days nts|month1=10|day1=22|year1=2019}}+ days ({{age in days nts|month1=11|day1=4|year1=2019}}+ days as recognized by WWE). [[Riddick Moss]]' reign is the longest singular reign at 41 days (40 days as recognized by WWE). Only seven other wrestlers have held the title for longer than a day: [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]], [[Drake Maverick]], [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]], [[Maria Kanellis]], [[Mojo Rawley]], and both [[The Singh Brothers|Singh Brothers]], Samir and Sunil. WWE announcer Mike Rome has the shortest reign, which lasted approximately 9 seconds. [[WWE Hall of Fame]]r [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]] is the oldest champion, winning the title at 78 years old (also making him the oldest title holder in WWE history), while [[Enes Kanter]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) is the youngest, winning the title at 27. Former WWE wrestler [[Kelly Kelly]] was the first of six women to have won the title. WWE Hall of Famer [[Ted DiBiase|\"The Million Dollar Man\" Ted DiBiase]] is the only title holder to become champion without winning the title; he purchased it from fellow Hall of Famer [[Alundra Blayze]], who was about to drop the belt into a trash can (reenacting the infamous incident of what she had done to the then-[[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] when she joined [[World Championship Wrestling]] in 1995). [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] ([[Scott Dawson (wrestler)|Scott Dawson]] and [[Dash Wilder]]) are the only tag team to win the title, being recognized as co-champions. Non-wrestlers to have held the title include [[Fox Sports|Fox]] sportscaster [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]], NBA player Enes Kanter, [[electronic music]] producer/[[disc jockey]] [[Marshmello]], WWE Senior Account Manager Michael Giaccio, [[NASCAR]] driver [[Kyle Busch]], and ''Raw'' announcer Mike Rome.<ref name=OfficialTitleHistory>{{cite web |url=https://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/24-7-championship|title=24/7 Championship|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe current champion is Mojo Rawley, who is in his seventh reign. He won the title by pinning R-Truth during [[WrestleMania 36]] Part 1, which [[Broadcast delay|aired]] on April 4, 2020; the event was taped on March 25 and March 26 in [[Orlando, Florida]], but it is currently unknown which day this title change was taped.\n\n== Reception==\nThe championship's reveal received a negative reaction from the live crowd, who booed it during the unveiling.<ref name=\"Raw05202019\"/> Foley said that the bad reception was probably due to the fans wanting to see the Hardcore Championship return as opposed to this new title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://solowrestling.mundodeportivo.com/new/80885-mick-foley-cree-que-su-promo-en-raw-estropeo-el-anuncio-del-campeonato-247|title=Mick Foley cree que su promo en Raw estrope\u00f3 el anuncio del Campeonato 24/7|trans-title=Mick Foley believes that his promo on Raw harmed the announcement of the 24/7 Championship|website=SoloWrestling|language=es|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> Foley was hopeful that it would bring back the fun and excitement that the Hardcore title had with its 24/7 rule, but without the same danger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/playlist/raw-may-20-2019-exclusives|title=Mick Foley on the unpredictability of the 24/7 Title: WWE.com Exclusive, May 20, 2019|date=May 20, 2019|work=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> Fellow WWE Hall of Famer [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]] said the concept was fun but the title \"[was] the ugliest championship ever created\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://superluchas.com/edge-del-campeonato-24-7-el-titulo-mas-feo-jamas-creado/|title=Edge: \"El Campeonato 24/7 es el t\u00edtulo m\u00e1s feo jam\u00e1s creado\"|trans-title=Edge: \"The 24/7 Championship is the ugliest title ever created\"|first=Jon|last=Duarte|website=[[S\u00faper Luchas]]|language=es|date=May 27, 2019|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref>  PWInsider's Mike Johnson liked the concept, but the introduction was \"silly\", since fans \"believed, just for a second, this belt was going to be something that was unveiled that brought a gritty, edge back\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=126643|title=IS THE 24/7 TITLE A WASTE OF TIME?, WHY THERE WAS COMMENTARY ON HART VS. MAGEE, WILLIE GILZENBERG & MORE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe title's popularity with the fans would subsequently improve: within weeks, the 24/7 Championship would get the highest viewed segments of both ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' on [[YouTube]], garnering millions of views each per video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwmania.com/247-title-segments-drawing-big-numbers-for-wwe|title=24/7 Title Segments Drawing Big Numbers For WWE|first=PWMania com|last=Staff|publisher=}}</ref> Multi-time 24/7 Champion R-Truth was voted by WWE fans as their favorite champion in June 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harris |first1=Jeffrey |title=WWE News: R-Truth Voted Favorite Champion by Fans, Bayley vs. Alexa Bliss Tale of the Tape, New WWE 365 Bonus Clip for Alexa Bliss |url=https://411mania.com/wrestling/wwe-r-truth-favorite-champion/ |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |work=411mania |date=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT ADD LINK TO HARDCORE CHAMPIONSHIP. IT IS ALREADY LINKED PREVIOUSLY IN THE ARTICLE. REFER TO WP:SEEALSO -->\n* [[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship]] \u2013 a title with a similar 24/7 rule\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/24-7-championship Official WWE 24/7 Championship title history]\n\n{{WWE 24/7 Championship}}\n{{WWE Championships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wwe 24/7 Championship}}\n\n[[Category:WWE championships]]\n[[Category:2019 introductions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professional wrestling championship}}\n{{pp-protected|reason=Persistent addition of [[WP:INTREF|unsourced or poorly sourced content]] to this article about a current event, based on the nature of this subject, seems like it's likely to continue. This is the 7th protection log entry in just over two months.|small=yes}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox professional wrestling championship\n| name           = WWE 24/7 Championship\n| image          = WWE_24-7_Championship_belt.png\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = The WWE 24/7 Championship belt\n| currentholder  = [[Mojo Rawley]]\n| won            = March 25 or 26, 2020\n| aired          = April 4, 2020\n| created        = May 20, 2019\n| promotion      = [[WWE]]\n| brand          = <!--It's all the brands. We only need to put them here if it is specific to certain ones.-->\n| firstchamp     = [[Titus O'Neil]]\n| mostreigns     = [[R-Truth]] (35 reigns)\n| longestreign   = [[Riddick Moss]] (41 days){{efn|40 days as recognized by WWE.}}\n| shortestreign  = [[Mike Rome]] (9 seconds)\n| oldest         = [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]] ({{Age in years and days|January 19, 1941|July 22, 2019}}) \n| youngest       = [[Enes Kanter]] ({{Age in years and days|May 20, 1992|September 9, 2019}})                                     \n| heaviest       = [[The Revival (professional wrestling)| The Revival]] {{small|([[Scott Dawson (wrestler)|Scott Dawson]] and [[Dash Wilder]])}} ({{convert|446|lb|kg|abbr=on}} combined)\n| lightest       = [[Kelly Kelly]] ({{Convert|108|lb|kg|0|abbr=on}})\n| pastnames      = \n}}\n\nThe '''WWE 24/7 Championship''' is a [[professional wrestling]] [[Professional wrestling championship#Weight class championships|championship]] created and promoted by the American [[professional wrestling promotion|promotion]] [[WWE]]. It is a tertiary championship open to anyone\u2014regardless of gender or WWE employment status\u2014and carries the special rule that it can be defended \"[[24/7]]\", as in any time, [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|anywhere]], as long as a WWE referee is present. Because of this rule, the championship is defended across all of WWE's brands\u2014[[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]], [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]], [[205 Live (WWE brand)|205 Live]], [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]], and [[NXT UK (WWE brand)|NXT UK]]\u2014as well as outside of regular shows, often with videos posted on the promotion's website and social media accounts. The current champion is [[Mojo Rawley]], who is in his seventh reign.\n\nThe title was unveiled by [[Mick Foley]] on the May 20, 2019 episode of ''[[Monday Night Raw]]'', where [[Titus O'Neil]] from Raw became the inaugural champion. It is similar to the previous [[WWE Hardcore Championship]], which also had a 24/7 rule. This rule can be temporarily suspended by an authority figure, usually done during a scheduled match for the title or matches that involve the champion.\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Titus O'Neal 2017.jpg|thumb|upright|Inaugural 24/7 Champion [[Titus O'Neil]]]]\nDuring the [[Money in the Bank (2019)|2019 Money in the Bank]] pay-per-view on May 19, [[WWE]] announced that a new championship would be introduced on the following night's episode of ''[[WWE Raw|Raw]]'',<ref name=\"MITB2019\">{{cite web|last=Powell|first=Jason|title=WWE Money in the Bank results: Powell's live review of Seth Rollins vs. AJ Styles for the WWE Universal Championship, Kofi Kingston vs. Kevin Owens for the WWE Championship, Becky Lynch defends the Raw and Smackdown Women's Titles, two Money in the Bank ladder matches|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/05/19/wwe-money-in-the-bank-results-powells-live-review-of-seth-rollins-vs-aj-styles-for-the-wwe-universal-championship-kofi-kingston-vs-kevin-owens-for-the-wwe-championship-becky-lynch-defends-the-r/|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=May 19, 2019|date=May 19, 2019}}</ref> where hardcore legend and [[WWE Hall of Fame]]r [[Mick Foley]] unveiled the WWE 24/7 Championship. Like the former [[WWE Hardcore Championship]] and its \"[[WWE Hardcore Championship#24/7 rule|24/7 rule]]\", the 24/7 Championship can be defended anytime, [[Professional wrestling match types#Falls Count Anywhere match|anywhere]], as long as a WWE referee is present,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vgr.com/wwe-24-7-championship-belt-debuts-on-raw-now-available-in-wwe-2k19-downloads/|title=WWE 24/7 Championship Belt Debuts on Raw, Now Available in WWE 2K19 Downloads|last=Couden|first=Matt|date=May 21, 2019|website=VGR|language=en|access-date=June 29, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Johnson\" /><ref name=\"24/7belt\" /> hence its name. Due to this, Foley said the title can be defended on [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]], [[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]], [[205 Live (WWE brand)|205 Live]], [[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]], and [[NXT UK (WWE brand)|NXT UK]]. He also said that WWE legends could return and challenge for the title. After the unveiling, Foley laid the title belt in the ring and said that whoever secured the championship first in a scramble would become the inaugural champion. Raw's [[Titus O'Neil]] became the inaugural champion by doing so, defeating [[Cedric Alexander]], [[Drake Maverick]], [[Ethan Carter III|EC3]], [[Eric Young (wrestler)|Eric Young]], [[Karl Anderson]], [[Luke Gallows]], [[Mojo Rawley]], and [[No Way Jose (wrestler)|No Way Jose]] to claim the championship.<ref name=\"Johnson\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/article/126603/wwes-newest-championship-is.html?p=1|title=WWE'S NEWEST CHAMPIONSHIP IS...|last=Johnson|first=Mike|publisher=PWInsider|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"24/7belt\">{{cite web|url=http://www.prowrestlingsheet.com/new-24-7-title-unveiling-video/#.XONkdS2ZNQI|title=WATCH: Mick Foley Unveils New WWE 24/7 Title, First Champion Crowned|last=Satin|first=Ryan|work=Pro Wrestling Sheet|date=May 20, 2019|accessdate=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Raw05202019\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pwtorch.com/site/2019/05/20/5-20-wwe-raw-results-kellers-report-on-money-in-the-bank-fallout-will-brock-lesnar-announce-his-intensions-mick-foley-reveals-new-wwe-title/|title=5/20 WWE Raw Results: Keller's report on Money in the Bank fallout, will Brock Lesnar announce his intensions, Mick Foley reveals new WWE Title|date=May 20, 2019|last=Keller|first=Wade|work=Pro Wrestling Torch|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> It was later confirmed that the title was not gender-exclusive and could also be won by non-WWE personnel after the respective wins of former female wrestler [[Kelly Kelly]] and [[Fox Sports|Fox]] sportscaster [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]].<ref name=\"Raw07222019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/07/22/7-22-wwe-raw-results-powells-review-raw-reunion-featuring-steve-austin-ric-flair-dx-hulk-hogan-and-many-more-alexa-bliss-talkshow-with-becky-lynch-the-build-to-summerslam-continues/|title=7/22 WWE Raw Results: Powell's review Raw Reunion featuring Steve Austin, Ric Flair, DX, Hulk Hogan, and many more, Alexa Bliss talkshow with Becky Lynch, the build to SummerSlam continues|date=July 22, 2019|last=Barnett|first=Jake|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=July 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FOX Founders Day\">{{cite web|last=Tedesco|first=Mike|title=WWE 24/7 Championship changes hands multiple times at FOX Founders Day event|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/136429-wwe-24-7-championship-changes-hands-multiple-times-at-fox-founders-day-event/|work=WrestleView|date=August 24, 2019|accessdate=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAlthough a stipulation of the championship, the 24/7 rule can be temporarily suspended by an authority figure. This usually occurs when the champion is involved in a non-title match. For example, after [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]] won the title from [[R-Truth]] on the May 28, 2019 episode of ''[[SmackDown Live]]'', [[Shane McMahon]] suspended the rule until after the scheduled tag team match later that same night, in which both Elias and Truth were involved.<ref name=\"SmackDown05282019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/05/28/5-28-wwe-smackdown-live-results-barnetts-review-of-kofi-kingston-vs-kevin-owens-in-a-non-title-match-bayley-vs-lacey-evans-in-a-non-title-match-dolph-ziggler-on-the-kevin-owens-show/|title=5/28 WWE Smackdown Live Results: Barnett's review of Kofi Kingston vs. Kevin Owens in a non-title match, Bayley vs. Lacey Evans in a non-title match, Dolph Ziggler on the Kevin Owens Show|date=May 28, 2019|last=Barnett|first=Jake|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 19, 2019}}</ref> The rule can also be suspended during an actual scheduled match for the title to prevent other wrestlers from getting involved. For example, when R-Truth unsuccessfully defended the title against Elias in a [[lumberjack match]] on the June 4 episode of ''SmackDown''.<ref name=\"SmackDown06042019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/06/04/6-4-wwe-smackdown-live-results-barnetts-review-of-goldbergs-appearance-final-hype-for-wwe-super-showdown-in-saudi-arabia-bayley-on-a-moment-of-bliss/|title=6/4 WWE Smackdown Live Results: Barnett's review of Goldberg's appearance, final hype for WWE Super Showdown in Saudi Arabia, Bayley on A Moment of Bliss|date=June 4, 2019|last=Barnett|first=Jake|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 5, 2019}}</ref> Another example is when reigning champion R-Truth was a guest on [[The Miz]]'s \"Miz TV\" and during a subsequent scheduled match against Drake Maverick, both on the June 24 episode of ''Raw''.<ref name=\"Raw06242019\">{{cite web|url=https://prowrestling.net/site/2019/06/24/6-24-wwe-raw-results-powells-review-of-u-s-champion-ricochet-vs-aj-styles-in-a-non-title-match-roman-reigns-vs-shane-mcmahon-and-drew-mcintyre-in-a-handicap-match-wwe-champion-kofi-kingston-vs/|title=6/24 WWE Raw Results: Powell's review of U.S. Champion Ricochet vs. AJ Styles in a non-title match, Roman Reigns vs. Shane McMahon and Drew McIntyre in a handicap match, WWE Champion Kofi Kingston vs. Sami Zayn in a non-title match|date=June 24, 2019|last=Powell|first=Jason|work=Pro Wrestling Dot Net|accessdate=June 25, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAccording to [[professional wrestling]] journalist [[Dave Meltzer]], the idea for the title was proposed by the [[USA Network]], where ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' had both aired (until ''SmackDown''{{'}}s move to [[FOX]] in October 2019), in an attempt to increase the ratings during ''Raw''{{'}}s third hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://solowrestling.mundodeportivo.com/new/80949-usa-network-ideo-el-campeonato-247-de-wwe|title=USA Network ide\u00f3 el Campeonato 24/7 de WWE|trans-title=USA Network devised the WWE 24/7 Championship|website=[[SoloWrestling]]|language=es|date=May 23, 2019|accessdate=May 23, 2019}}</ref> The viewership of both shows had been declining; the April 29 and 30, 2019, episodes of ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'', respectively, both reached a record low for non-holiday broadcasts outside of football season,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alfredkonuwa/2019/05/03/wwes-viewership-is-tanking-fast-with-no-signs-of-slowing-down/#464a92927a3f|title=WWE's Viewership Is Tanking Fast With No Signs Of Slowing Down|date=May 3, 2019|last=Konuwa|first=Alfred|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> with viewership dropping off the most during ''Raw''{{'}}s third hour.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wrestleview.com/wwe-news/129104-wwe-raw-ratings-viewers-down-again-april-29-third-hour-drop-sets-a-record-low/|title=WWE RAW Ratings: Viewers down again April 29, Third hour drop sets a record low|date=April 30, 2019|last=Tedesco|first=Mike|work=[[WrestleView]]|accessdate=May 29, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn October 2019, Meltzer reported that following the [[2019 WWE Draft]], the title would only appear on ''Raw'' as ''SmackDown'' was moving to FOX and the title was USA Network's idea. Although the title was established under the rule that it could be defended on any brand, it has primarily only appeared on ''Raw'' since that draft, though a couple of non-Raw wrestlers have won the title since then.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://theringreport.com/wwe/backstage-news-on-the-24-7-championship-being-on-raw-and-wwe-keeping-couples-together-in-the-draft-a12286|title=Backstage News On The 24/7 Championship Being On RAW And WWE Keeping Couples Together In The Draft|date=October 15, 2019|last=Wilding|first=Josh|work=theringreport.com|accessdate=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Belt design==\nThe championship belt design features three gold plates on a green leather strap. The circular center plate prominently states \"24/7\" at the center (\"24\" and \"7\" written in green). The WWE logo is affixed at the top while the word \"CHAMPION\" is written along the edge of the bottom half of the center plate. The two side plates, one on either side of the center plate, are rectangular. Unlike most of WWE's other championship belts, the side plates cannot be customized with the current champion's logos. They are mostly blank but with a simple ornate design on the bottom inner corner and top outer corner of each.<ref name=\"24/7belt\"/> As the belt lacks customizable side plates, Drake Maverick placed stickers that said \"Maverick 24:7\" in the blank space of the side plates,<ref>{{cite tweet|user=WWEMaverick|author=[[Drake Maverick]]|number=1146084264469049344|date=July 2, 2019|title=Side plates}}</ref> while [[Samir Singh]] placed stickers that spelled \"Bollywood\" around the center plate.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=SinghBrosWWE|author=[[The Singh Brothers]]|number=1195381214678568961|date=November 15, 2019|title=Longest reigning 24/7 Champion in WWE history!}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet|user=WWE|author=[[WWE]]|number=1196651601642962944|date=November 18, 2019|title=Ladies and gentlemen, your NEW 24/7 Champion... R-Truth! Watch how it all went down backstage! This night went from bad to worse for The Singh Brothers on RAW!}}</ref>\n\n== Reigns ==\n{{Main article|List of WWE 24/7 Champions}}\nAs of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTDAY}}, {{CURRENTYEAR}}, there have been 94 recognized reigns between 35 different people. [[R-Truth]] has the most reigns at 35 and the longest combined reign at {{age in days nts|month1=10|day1=22|year1=2019}}+ days ({{age in days nts|month1=11|day1=4|year1=2019}}+ days as recognized by WWE). [[Riddick Moss]]' reign is the longest singular reign at 41 days (40 days as recognized by WWE). Only seven other wrestlers have held the title for longer than a day: [[Carmella (wrestler)|Carmella]], [[Drake Maverick]], [[Elias (wrestler)|Elias]], [[Maria Kanellis]], [[Mojo Rawley]], and both [[The Singh Brothers|Singh Brothers]], Samir and Sunil. WWE announcer Mike Rome has the shortest reign, which lasted approximately 9 seconds. [[WWE Hall of Fame]]r [[Pat Patterson (wrestler)|Pat Patterson]] is the oldest champion, winning the title at 78 years old (also making him the oldest title holder in WWE history), while [[Enes Kanter]] of the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA) is the youngest, winning the title at 27. Former WWE wrestler [[Kelly Kelly]] was the first of six women to have won the title. WWE Hall of Famer [[Ted DiBiase|\"The Million Dollar Man\" Ted DiBiase]] is the only title holder to become champion without winning the title; he purchased it from fellow Hall of Famer [[Alundra Blayze]], who was about to drop the belt into a trash can (reenacting the infamous incident of what she had done to the then-[[WWE Women's Championship (1956\u20132010)|WWF Women's Championship]] when she joined [[World Championship Wrestling]] in 1995). [[The Revival (professional wrestling)|The Revival]] ([[Scott Dawson (wrestler)|Scott Dawson]] and [[Dash Wilder]]) are the only tag team to win the title, being recognized as co-champions. Non-wrestlers to have held the title include [[Fox Sports|Fox]] sportscaster [[Rob Stone (sportscaster)|Rob Stone]], NBA player Enes Kanter, [[electronic music]] producer/[[disc jockey]] [[Marshmello]], WWE Senior Account Manager Michael Giaccio, [[NASCAR]] driver [[Kyle Busch]], and ''Raw'' announcer Mike Rome.<ref name=OfficialTitleHistory>{{cite web |url=https://www.wwe.com/classics/titlehistory/24-7-championship|title=24/7 Championship|publisher=WWE|accessdate=June 28, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe current champion is Mojo Rawley, who is in his seventh reign. He won the title by pinning R-Truth during [[WrestleMania 36]] Part 1, which [[Broadcast delay|aired]] on April 4, 2020; the event was taped on March 25 and March 26 in [[Orlando, Florida]], but it is currently unknown which day this match was taped.\n\n== Reception==\nThe championship's reveal received a negative reaction from the live crowd, who booed it during the unveiling.<ref name=\"Raw05202019\"/> Foley said that the bad reception was probably due to the fans wanting to see the Hardcore Championship return as opposed to this new title.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://solowrestling.mundodeportivo.com/new/80885-mick-foley-cree-que-su-promo-en-raw-estropeo-el-anuncio-del-campeonato-247|title=Mick Foley cree que su promo en Raw estrope\u00f3 el anuncio del Campeonato 24/7|trans-title=Mick Foley believes that his promo on Raw harmed the announcement of the 24/7 Championship|website=SoloWrestling|language=es|date=May 21, 2019|accessdate=May 21, 2019}}</ref> Foley was hopeful that it would bring back the fun and excitement that the Hardcore title had with its 24/7 rule, but without the same danger.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/playlist/raw-may-20-2019-exclusives|title=Mick Foley on the unpredictability of the 24/7 Title: WWE.com Exclusive, May 20, 2019|date=May 20, 2019|work=[[WWE]].com|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> Fellow WWE Hall of Famer [[Edge (wrestler)|Edge]] said the concept was fun but the title \"[was] the ugliest championship ever created\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://superluchas.com/edge-del-campeonato-24-7-el-titulo-mas-feo-jamas-creado/|title=Edge: \"El Campeonato 24/7 es el t\u00edtulo m\u00e1s feo jam\u00e1s creado\"|trans-title=Edge: \"The 24/7 Championship is the ugliest title ever created\"|first=Jon|last=Duarte|website=[[S\u00faper Luchas]]|language=es|date=May 27, 2019|accessdate=May 27, 2019}}</ref>  PWInsider's Mike Johnson liked the concept, but the introduction was \"silly\", since fans \"believed, just for a second, this belt was going to be something that was unveiled that brought a gritty, edge back\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pwinsider.com/ViewArticle.php?id=126643|title=IS THE 24/7 TITLE A WASTE OF TIME?, WHY THERE WAS COMMENTARY ON HART VS. MAGEE, WILLIE GILZENBERG & MORE|last=Johnson|first=Mike|publisher=PWInsider|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe title's popularity with the fans would subsequently improve: within weeks, the 24/7 Championship would get the highest viewed segments of both ''Raw'' and ''SmackDown'' on [[YouTube]], garnering millions of views each per video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pwmania.com/247-title-segments-drawing-big-numbers-for-wwe|title=24/7 Title Segments Drawing Big Numbers For WWE|first=PWMania com|last=Staff|publisher=}}</ref> Multi-time 24/7 Champion R-Truth was voted by WWE fans as their favorite champion in June 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Harris |first1=Jeffrey |title=WWE News: R-Truth Voted Favorite Champion by Fans, Bayley vs. Alexa Bliss Tale of the Tape, New WWE 365 Bonus Clip for Alexa Bliss |url=https://411mania.com/wrestling/wwe-r-truth-favorite-champion/ |accessdate=June 26, 2019 |work=411mania |date=June 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n<!-- PLEASE DO NOT ADD LINK TO HARDCORE CHAMPIONSHIP. IT IS ALREADY LINKED PREVIOUSLY IN THE ARTICLE. REFER TO WP:SEEALSO -->\n* [[Ironman Heavymetalweight Championship]] \u2013 a title with a similar 24/7 rule\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n;Notes\n{{notelist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://www.wwe.com/titlehistory/24-7-championship Official WWE 24/7 Championship title history]\n\n{{WWE 24/7 Championship}}\n{{WWE Championships}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wwe 24/7 Championship}}\n\n[[Category:WWE championships]]\n[[Category:2019 introductions]]\n", "name_user": "JDC808", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReigns", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WWE_24/7_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Signal Studios", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Signal Studios\n| logo             = [[File:Signal Studios logo.png|frameless]]\n| caption          = \n| type             = \n| traded_as        = \n| genre            = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2008}}\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = [[Seattle]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|signalstudios.net/}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''''Signal Studios''''' is a developer of both [[video games]] and interactive software applications. The studio was founded by industry veterans, with experience working at some of the world's top studios and publishers, combining many years of knowledge across all disciplines of the games industry.<ref name=\"SignalCompany\">http://www.signalstudios.net/company</ref>\n\nSignal is best known for their hit game, [[Toy Soldiers (video game)|Toy Soldiers]], one of the top 10 best-selling [[Xbox Live Arcade|XBLA]] games of all time. As part of the Toy Soldiers Franchise, they have also released [[Toy Soldiers: Cold War]] and a number of DLCs for both titles. At [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3]] 2012, the studio announced their first action RPG, [[Ascend: Hand of Kul]].\n\nThe studio is currently located in [[Kirkland, Washington]] with over 40 employees.\n\n==History==\nIn January 2008, Signal Studios was founded in [[Bothell, Washington]] by 3 individuals. Their first office was a house along the banks of the [[Sammamish River]]. In 2010, Signal relocated to a larger office building on the North Creek of Bothell. In 2012, the company moved to [[Kirkland, Washington]], to reside in the offices of the now defunct [[Sandblast Games]].<ref name=\"moved\">http://www.signalstudios.net/events/we-moved-now-the-famous-wargame-from-kirkland/</ref>\n\n==Games==\nSignal has released several games, as well as additional [[downloadable content]] (DLC), for both [[Xbox 360]] ([[Xbox Live Arcade|XBLA]]) and [[Windows]].<ref name=\"SignalGames\" >http://www.signalstudios.net/games</ref>\n\n'''2010'''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers (video game)|Toy Soldiers]]'' (Xbox 360 + PC)\n** Kaiser's Battle DLC\n** Invasion DLC\n\n'''2011'''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers: Cold War]]'' (Xbox 360) - ''featured in XBLA's [[Summer of Arcade]] 2011''\n** Evil Empire DLC\n** Napalm DLC\n\n'''2013'''\n* ''[[Ascend: Hand of Kul]]''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers: Complete]]''\n\n'''2015'''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers: War Chest]]'' (PlayStation 4, Xbox One, PC)\n\n==Technology==\nSignal Studios uses an engine that was specifically designed for the development of multi-platform 3D games and simulations, called SigEngine. This suite of tools and features includes a clean object-oriented code base, a level design and entity creation tool (SigEd), modeling package plugins, shader and material editors (SigShade and MatEd), and an animation engine with a powerful script interface (SigAnim).<ref name=SignalCompany />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Kirkland, Washington]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{US-entertainment-company-stub}}\n{{US-videogame-company-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name             = Signal Studios\n| logo             = [[File:Signal Studios logo.png|frameless]]\n| caption          = \n| type             = \n| traded_as        = \n| genre            = <!-- Only used with media and publishing companies -->\n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = {{Start date|2008}}\n| founder          = \n| defunct          = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| location_city    = [[Seattle]]\n| location_country = [[United States]]\n| locations        = \n| area_served      = \n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Video game industry|Video games]]\n| products         = \n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income       = \n| aum              = <!-- Only used with financial services companies -->\n| assets           = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{URL|signalstudios.net/}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''''Signal Studios''''' is a developer of both [[video games]] and interactive software applications. The studio was founded by industry veterans, with experience working at some of the world\u2019s top studios and publishers, combining many years of knowledge across all disciplines of the games industry.<ref name=\"SignalCompany\">http://www.signalstudios.net/company</ref>\n\nSignal is best known for their hit game, [[Toy Soldiers (video game)|Toy Soldiers]], one of the top 10 best-selling [[Xbox Live Arcade|XBLA]] games of all time. As part of the Toy Soldiers Franchise, they have also released [[Toy Soldiers: Cold War]] and a number of DLCs for both titles. At [[Electronic Entertainment Expo|E3]] 2012, the studio announced their first action RPG, [[Ascend: Hand of Kul]].\n\nThe studio is currently located in [[Kirkland, Washington]] with over 40 employees.\n\n==History==\nIn January 2008, Signal Studios was founded in [[Bothell, Washington]] by 3 individuals. Their first office was a house along the banks of the [[Sammamish River]]. In 2010, Signal relocated to a larger office building on the North Creek of Bothell. In 2012, the company moved to [[Kirkland, Washington]], to reside in the offices of the now defunct [[Sandblast Games]].<ref name=\"moved\">http://www.signalstudios.net/events/we-moved-now-the-famous-wargame-from-kirkland/</ref>\n\n==Games==\nSignal has released several games, as well as additional [[downloadable content]] (DLC), for both [[Xbox 360]] ([[Xbox Live Arcade|XBLA]]) and [[Windows]].<ref name=\"SignalGames\" >http://www.signalstudios.net/games</ref>\n\n'''2010'''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers (video game)|Toy Soldiers]]'' (Xbox 360 + PC)\n** Kaiser's Battle DLC\n** Invasion DLC\n\n'''2011'''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers: Cold War]]'' (Xbox 360) - ''featured in XBLA's [[Summer of Arcade]] 2011''\n** Evil Empire DLC\n** Napalm DLC\n\n'''2013'''\n* ''[[Ascend: Hand of Kul]]''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers: Complete]]''\n\n'''2015'''\n* ''[[Toy Soldiers: War Chest]]'' (PlayStation 4, Xbox One, PC)\n\n==Technology==\nSignal Studios uses an engine that was specifically designed for the development of multi-platform 3D games and simulations, called SigEngine. This suite of tools and features includes a clean object-oriented code base, a level design and entity creation tool (SigEd), modeling package plugins, shader and material editors (SigShade and MatEd), and an animation engine with a powerful script interface (SigAnim).<ref name=SignalCompany />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Video game companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Video game development companies]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Kirkland, Washington]]\n[[Category:Video game companies established in 2009]]\n[[Category:Entertainment companies established in 2009]]\n\n\n{{US-entertainment-company-stub}}\n{{US-videogame-company-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Nealbo", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signal_Studios"}
{"title_page": "Hare Trigger", "text_new": "{{Infobox Hollywood cartoon\n|name = Hare Trigger\n|image = File:HareTrigger Lobby Card.png\n|caption = Lobby card\n|producer = [[Edward Selzer]] (unc.)\n|director = [[Friz Freleng|I. Freleng]]\n|story = [[Michael Maltese]]\n|animator = [[Manuel Perez (animator)|Manuel Perez]]<br />Ken Champin<br />[[Virgil Ross]]<br />[[Gerry Chiniquy]]<br />[[Jack Bradbury]] (unc.)\n|layout_artist = [[Hawley Pratt]]\n|background_artist = [[Paul Julian (artist)|Paul Julian]]\n|starring = [[Mel Blanc]]\n|music = [[Carl W. Stalling]]\n|studio = [[Warner Bros. Cartoons]]\n|distributor = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]<br />[[The Vitaphone Corporation]]\n|released = May 5, 1945 (USA)\n|color_process = [[Technicolor]]\n|runtime = 8:00\n|language = [[English language|English]]\n}}\n\n'''''Hare Trigger''''' is a 1945 ''[[Merrie Melodies]]'' directed by [[Friz Freleng]], and stars [[Bugs Bunny]].<ref name=Beck>{{cite book |last1=Beck |first1=Jerry |last2=Friedwald |first2=Will |title=Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies: A Complete Illustrated Guide to the Warner Bros. Cartoons |date=1989 |publisher=Henry Holt and Co |isbn=0-8050-0894-2 |page=159}}</ref> The short featured the first appearance of [[Yosemite Sam]], as well as the first short to credit (almost) the whole animation staff who worked on the short (previously, shorts credited the director, one animator, writer, musical director and sometimes the voice actor).\n\nThe shorts also the first to use the shortened version of [[Merrily We Roll Along (song)|Merrily We Roll Along]] that played from 1945, to 1955. The title is a play on \"hair trigger\", referring to any weapon or other device with a sensitive trigger.\n\n==Plot==\nAfter opening credits underscored by a lively instrumental of \"[[Cheyenne (1906 song)|Cheyenne]]\", an old-fashioned train is seen rolling along through the desert. It passes another train going around a utility pole, and voices are heard repeating \"[[Bread and butter (superstition)|Bread and Butter]]\" with the engine blowing its whistle to a tune called \"Yankee Doodle\".\n\nBugs is riding in the mail car of a train, singing a nonsense song called [http://www.kididdles.com/lyrics/g002.html \"Go Get the Axe\"], when a pint-sized bandit attempts to rob the train (with the underscore playing stereotypical \"villain music\"), only to have it pass clear over his head. He then calls for his horse, which he needs a rolling step-stair to mount. He catches up and boards the train and begins to rob it while the mail clerk wraps himself in a package marked ''DON'T OPEN 'TIL [[XMAS]]''. The bandit accidentally throws Bugs Bunny in his sack. Bugs assumes he's [[Jesse James]]. The bandit scoffs and tells him (and the audience), \"I'm Yosemite Sam, the meanest, toughest, rip-roarin'-est, [[Edward Everett Horton]]-est ''hombre'' what ever packed a six-shooter!\" (This pattern of Sam introducing himself to Bugs and the audience continued in other cartoons.) Bugs tells Sam that there is another tough guy in the train packing a \"seven-shooter\", and Sam goes looking for him \u2013 and it's Bugs in disguise.\n\nVarious fights ensue, as each character temporarily gets the upper hand for a while. In one scene, Bugs dumps red ink on Sam, compelling him to think he's been shot; he collapses but eventually gets the joke. Sam pushes his face furiously into Bugs', then pulls back and with a quiet, offended tone asks, \"Why did you pour ink on mah haid?\"  After another skirmish, Bugs tricks Sam into dashing into a lounge car in which a horrific fight is occurring. Stock film footage of a stereotypical western saloon fight (taken from the Warner Bros. western film ''[[Dodge City (film)|Dodge City]]'', was used here). With the sounds of crashes and bangs in the background, Bugs calmly sings \"[[Sweet Georgia Brown]]\" to himself. Sam emerges tottering, banged and bruised, to a comical instrumental of \"[[Battle Cry of Freedom|Rally 'Round the Flag]]\", and a gag occurs where Bugs affects the stereotyped voice of an African-American train porter, and has the dazed Sam convinced he's supposed to disembark the train, piling him up with luggage; Sam even hands Bugs a silver coin as a tip, and Bugs says, \"Thank you, suh!\" As Sam steps off the moving train, the mail-drop hook grabs him and temporarily whisks him off the train. Bugs thinks he has vanquished Sam, and yells, \"So long, screwy, see ya in [[St. Louis|Saint Louie]]!\" a line that will be echoed in ''[[Wild and Woolly Hare]]'' and ''[[A Feather in His Hare]]''. But Sam gets back on board somehow. Bugs and Sam start a fight on top of the passenger carriages.\n\nFinally, Sam has Bugs tied up, dangling from a rope, weighted down by an anvil, and fiendishly cutting through the rope, while the train is passing over a gorge. (\"Now, ya lop-eared polecat, try and get out of ''this'' one!\") The screen fills with the words the narrator ([[Mel Blanc]], in close to his natural voice) is saying, \"Is this the end of Bugs Bunny? Will our hero be dashed to bits on the jagged rocks below?\" and so on. Then Bugs walks across the screen, dressed in top hat and tails, carrying a bag full of gold (reward money), and dragging the now tied-up Sam behind him, mocking the on-screen words (\"Is he to be doomed to utter destruction? Will he be rendered [[non compos mentis]]?\"). Bugs closes by turning to the audience and repeating a popular radio catch-phrase from [[Red Skelton]]'s \"Mean Widdle Kid\": \"He don't know me vewy well, do he?\" as a bar of \"[[Kingdom Coming]]\" plays on the track at [[Iris shot|iris-out]].\n\n==Availability==\n* VHS \u2013 ''Bugs Bunny Classics: Special Collectors Edition''\n* VHS \u2013 ''Bugs Bunny's Zaniest Toons''\n* VHS \u2013 ''[[The Golden Age of Looney Tunes]]'' Vol 6: Friz Freleng\n* Laserdisc \u2013 ''Bugs Bunny Classics: Special Collectors Edition''\n* Laserdisc \u2013 ''[[The Golden Age of Looney Tunes]]'' Volume 1, Side 6\n* DVD \u2013 ''[[Looney Tunes Golden Collection: Volume 6]]'', Disc 1\n\n==See also==\n* [[Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies filmography (1940\u20131949)]]\n* [[List of Bugs Bunny cartoons]]\n* [[List of Yosemite Sam cartoons]]\n\n==Notes==\n*The engines on both trains are [[4-4-0]]s or American type locomotives, which were the most common wheel arrangements for locomotives, during the 1800s on American railroads, despite the engine being a [[2-4-0]], converted to a 2-4-0.\n*\"Hare Trigger\" contains the first appearance of [[Yosemite Sam]], who would go on to be one of [[Bugs Bunny]]'s most frequent rivals, after [[Elmer Fudd]]. Freleng created Yosemite Sam because he thought Elmer Fudd was too stupid and soft and he needed a smarter and tougher foe for Bugs. The character was well received and would go on to star in thirty-two more shorts in the Golden Age.\n*This is the first cartoon with the 1945-55 opening rendition of ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (song)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''.\n*This is the first cartoon with full credits.\n*This is also the first Bugs Bunny cartoon with the \"Bugs Bunny in\" opening.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|37765}}\n* {{bcdb title|559}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|before = [[The Unruly Hare]]\n|title = [[List of Bugs Bunny cartoons|Bugs Bunny Cartoons]]\n|years = 1945\n|after = [[Hare Conditioned]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Friz Freleng}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hare Trigger}}\n[[Category:1945 films]]\n[[Category:1945 short films]]\n[[Category:1945 animated films]]\n[[Category:1940s American animated films]]\n[[Category:1940s animated short films]]\n[[Category:1940s Western (genre) comedy films]]\n[[Category:Merrie Melodies shorts]]\n[[Category:Short films directed by Friz Freleng]]\n[[Category:Films set on trains]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated western (genre) animation]]\n[[Category:American animated short films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring Bugs Bunny]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Hollywood cartoon\n|name = Hare Trigger\n|image = File:HareTrigger Lobby Card.png\n|caption = Lobby card\n|producer = [[Edward Selzer]] (unc.)\n|director = [[Friz Freleng|I. Freleng]]\n|story = [[Michael Maltese]]\n|animator = [[Manuel Perez (animator)|Manuel Perez]]<br />Ken Champin<br />[[Virgil Ross]]<br />[[Gerry Chiniquy]]<br />[[Jack Bradbury]] (unc.)\n|layout_artist = [[Hawley Pratt]]\n|background_artist = [[Paul Julian (artist)|Paul Julian]]\n|starring = [[Mel Blanc]]\n|music = [[Carl W. Stalling]]\n|studio = [[Warner Bros. Cartoons]]\n|distributor = [[Warner Bros. Pictures]]<br />[[The Vitaphone Corporation]]\n|released = May 5, 1945 (USA)\n|color_process = [[Technicolor]]\n|runtime = 8:00\n|language = [[English language|English]]\n}}\n\n'''''Hare Trigger''''' is a 1945 ''[[Merrie Melodies]]'' directed by [[Friz Freleng]], and stars [[Bugs Bunny]].<ref name=Beck>{{cite book |last1=Beck |first1=Jerry |last2=Friedwald |first2=Will |title=Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies: A Complete Illustrated Guide to the Warner Bros. Cartoons |date=1989 |publisher=Henry Holt and Co |isbn=0-8050-0894-2 |page=159}}</ref> The short featured the first appearance of [[Yosemite Sam]], as well as the first short to credit (almost) the whole animation staff who worked on the short (previously, shorts credited the director, one animator, writer, musical director and sometimes the voice actor).\n\nThe shorts also the first to use the shortened version of [[Merrily We Roll Along (song) | Merrily We Roll Along]] that played from 1945, to 1955. The title is a play on \"hair trigger\", referring to any weapon or other device with a sensitive trigger.\n\n==Plot==\nAfter opening credits underscored by a lively instrumental of \"[[Cheyenne (1906 song)|Cheyenne]]\", an old-fashioned train is seen rolling along through the desert. It passes another train going around a utility pole, and voices are heard repeating \"[[Bread and butter (superstition)|Bread and Butter]]\" with the engine blowing its whistle to a tune called \"Yankee Doodle\".\n\nBugs is riding in the mail car of a train, singing a nonsense song called [http://www.kididdles.com/lyrics/g002.html \"Go Get the Axe\"], when a pint-sized bandit attempts to rob the train (with the underscore playing stereotypical \"villain music\"), only to have it pass clear over his head. He then calls for his horse, which he needs a rolling step-stair to mount. He catches up and boards the train and begins to rob it while the mail clerk wraps himself in a package marked ''DON'T OPEN 'TIL [[XMAS]]''. The bandit accidentally throws Bugs Bunny in his sack. Bugs assumes he's [[Jesse James]]. The bandit scoffs and tells him (and the audience), \"I'm Yosemite Sam, the meanest, toughest, rip-roarin'-est, [[Edward Everett Horton]]-est ''hombre'' what ever packed a six-shooter!\" (This pattern of Sam introducing himself to Bugs and the audience continued in other cartoons.) Bugs tells Sam that there is another tough guy in the train packing a \"seven-shooter\", and Sam goes looking for him \u2013 and it's Bugs in disguise.\n\nVarious fights ensue, as each character temporarily gets the upper hand for a while. In one scene, Bugs dumps red ink on Sam, compelling him to think he's been shot; he collapses but eventually gets the joke. Sam pushes his face furiously into Bugs', then pulls back and with a quiet, offended tone asks, \"Why did you pour ink on mah haid?\"  After another skirmish, Bugs tricks Sam into dashing into a lounge car in which a horrific fight is occurring. Stock film footage of a stereotypical western saloon fight (taken from the Warner Bros. western film ''[[Dodge City (film)|Dodge City]]'', was used here). With the sounds of crashes and bangs in the background, Bugs calmly sings \"[[Sweet Georgia Brown]]\" to himself. Sam emerges tottering, banged and bruised, to a comical instrumental of \"[[Battle Cry of Freedom|Rally 'Round the Flag]]\", and a gag occurs where Bugs affects the stereotyped voice of an African-American train porter, and has the dazed Sam convinced he's supposed to disembark the train, piling him up with luggage; Sam even hands Bugs a silver coin as a tip, and Bugs says, \"Thank you, suh!\" As Sam steps off the moving train, the mail-drop hook grabs him and temporarily whisks him off the train. Bugs thinks he has vanquished Sam, and yells, \"So long, screwy, see ya in [[St. Louis|Saint Louie]]!\" a line that will be echoed in ''[[Wild and Woolly Hare]]'' and ''[[A Feather in His Hare]]''. But Sam gets back on board somehow. Bugs and Sam start a fight on top of the passenger carriages.\n\nFinally, Sam has Bugs tied up, dangling from a rope, weighted down by an anvil, and fiendishly cutting through the rope, while the train is passing over a gorge. (\"Now, ya lop-eared polecat, try and get out of ''this'' one!\") The screen fills with the words the narrator ([[Mel Blanc]], in close to his natural voice) is saying, \"Is this the end of Bugs Bunny? Will our hero be dashed to bits on the jagged rocks below?\" and so on. Then Bugs walks across the screen, dressed in top hat and tails, carrying a bag full of gold (reward money), and dragging the now tied-up Sam behind him, mocking the on-screen words (\"Is he to be doomed to utter destruction? Will he be rendered [[non compos mentis]]?\"). Bugs closes by turning to the audience and repeating a popular radio catch-phrase from [[Red Skelton]]'s \"Mean Widdle Kid\": \"He don't know me vewy well, do he?\" as a bar of \"[[Kingdom Coming]]\" plays on the track at [[Iris shot|iris-out]].\n\n==Availability==\n* VHS \u2013 ''Bugs Bunny Classics: Special Collectors Edition''\n* VHS \u2013 ''Bugs Bunny's Zaniest Toons''\n* VHS \u2013 ''[[The Golden Age of Looney Tunes]]'' Vol 6: Friz Freleng\n* Laserdisc \u2013 ''Bugs Bunny Classics: Special Collectors Edition''\n* Laserdisc \u2013 ''[[The Golden Age of Looney Tunes]]'' Volume 1, Side 6\n* DVD \u2013 ''[[Looney Tunes Golden Collection: Volume 6]]'', Disc 1\n\n==See also==\n* [[Looney Tunes and Merrie Melodies filmography (1940\u20131949)]]\n* [[List of Bugs Bunny cartoons]]\n* [[List of Yosemite Sam cartoons]]\n\n==Notes==\n*The engines on both trains are [[4-4-0]]s or American type locomotives, which were the most common wheel arrangements for locomotives, during the 1800s on American railroads, despite the engine being a [[2-4-0]], converted to a 2-4-0.\n*\"Hare Trigger\" contains the first appearance of [[Yosemite Sam]], who would go on to be one of [[Bugs Bunny]]'s most frequent rivals, after [[Elmer Fudd]]. Freleng created Yosemite Sam because he thought Elmer Fudd was too stupid and soft and he needed a smarter and tougher foe for Bugs. The character was well received and would go on to star in thirty-two more shorts in the Golden Age.\n*This is the first cartoon with the 1945-55 opening rendition of ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (song)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''.\n*This is the first cartoon with full credits.\n*This is also the first Bugs Bunny cartoon with the \"Bugs Bunny in\" opening.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|37765}}\n* {{bcdb title|559}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n|before = [[The Unruly Hare]]\n|title = [[List of Bugs Bunny cartoons|Bugs Bunny Cartoons]]\n|years = 1945\n|after = [[Hare Conditioned]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Friz Freleng}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hare Trigger}}\n[[Category:1945 films]]\n[[Category:1945 short films]]\n[[Category:1945 animated films]]\n[[Category:1940s American animated films]]\n[[Category:1940s animated short films]]\n[[Category:1940s Western (genre) comedy films]]\n[[Category:Merrie Melodies shorts]]\n[[Category:Short films directed by Friz Freleng]]\n[[Category:Films set on trains]]\n[[Category:American Western (genre) comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Animated western (genre) animation]]\n[[Category:American animated short films]]\n[[Category:Films featuring Bugs Bunny]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hare_Trigger"}
{"title_page": "Maraschino cherry", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates |date=February 2016}}\n{{About|the fruit|the film by Radley Metzger|Maraschino Cherry (film)}}\n[[File:Maraschino cherries.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Maraschino cherries]]\n[[File:Real maraschino cherries.jpg|thumb|Two [[Girolamo Luxardo|Luxardo]]-brand maraschino cherries are shown impaled on a cocktail pick atop a jar of more of the same cherries in syrup. Some high-end brands of maraschino cherries such as those pictured omit the ubiquitous bright red dye, opting for a darker colored product.]]\n[[File:Whiskey_sour_in_coupe_glass_with_garnishes.jpg|thumb|A [[whiskey sour]] garnished with two [[Girolamo Luxardo|Luxardo]]-brand maraschino cherries in addition to other garnishes.]]\n[[File:Tequila Sunrise glass.jpg|thumb|A [[Tequila Sunrise (cocktail)|Tequila Sunrise]] cocktail [[Garnish (food)|garnished]] with a maraschino cherry]]\n[[File:Macromaraschino.jpg|thumb|Close-up, maraschino cherry]]\nA '''maraschino cherry''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u00e6r|\u0259|\u02c8|s|k|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}} {{respell|marr-\u0259|SKEE|noh}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u00e6r|\u0259|\u02c8|\u0283|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}} {{respell|marr-\u0259|SHEE|noh}}) is a preserved, sweetened [[cherry]], typically made from light-colored sweet cherries such as the [[Royal Ann cherry|Royal Ann]],<ref>{{cite book | last=Murray | first=M.T. | last2=Pizzorno | first2=J. | last3=Pizzorno | first3=L. | title=The Encyclopedia of Healing Foods | publisher=Atria Books | year=2010 | isbn=978-1-4391-0344-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UKtAMVUT57EC&pg=PA264 | access-date=August 25, 2018 | page=264}}</ref> [[Rainier cherry|Rainier]], or Gold varieties. In their modern form, the cherries are first preserved in a [[brine]] solution usually containing [[sulfur dioxide]] and [[calcium chloride]] to bleach the fruit, then soaked in a [[Suspension (chemistry)|suspension]] of [[food coloring]] (common red food dye is [[Allura Red AC|FD&C Red 40]]), [[sugar syrup]], and other components.<ref name=who>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Who Made That Maraschino Cherry? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/who-made-that-maraschino-cherry.html |quote= In 1925, Wiegand discovered that adding calcium salts to the preserving brine firmed up the fruit. |newspaper=[[New York Times Magazine]] |date=September 19, 2014 |accessdate=2015-02-20 }}</ref>\n\nMaraschino cherries are an ingredient in many [[cocktail]]s, giving them the nickname \"cocktail cherries\". As a [[Garnish (food)|garnish]], they often are used to decorate [[frozen yogurt]], baked [[ham]], [[cake]]s, [[pastry]], [[parfait]]s, [[milkshake]]s, [[sundae|ice cream sundaes]], and [[ice cream soda]]s. They are an integral part of an American [[ice cream sundae]]. The term \"cherry on top\" refers to the Maraschino cherries on top of the ice cream sundae. They are frequently included in canned [[fruit cocktail]].<ref>[[USDA]]'s [http://www.ams.usda.gov/AMSv1.0/getfile?dDocName=STELPRD3105806 Grading Manual for Canned Fruit Cocktail]</ref> Sometimes the cherries, along with some of the maraschino syrup, are put into a glass of [[Coca-Cola]] to make an old-fashioned or homemade \"[[Cherry Coke]]\".\n\n==Europe==\nThe name ''maraschino'' originates from the [[Marasca cherry]] of [[Croatian cuisine|Croatian]] origin<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whatscookingamerica.net/History/MaraschinoCherry.htm|title=The fruit that made Oregon famous! (in Maraschino Cherry History)|last=Verzemnieks|first=Inara|date=February 12, 2006|work=The Oregonian|via=What's Cooking America website|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref> and the [[maraschino]] [[liqueur]] made from it, in which Marasca cherries were crushed and preserved after being pickled.<ref name=\"Blech 2009\">{{cite book | last=Blech | first=Z.Y. | title=Kosher Food Production | publisher=Wiley | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8138-0480-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=smFVSUWXTbkC&pg=PA266 | access-date=August 25, 2018 | page=266}}</ref> Whole cherries preserved in this liqueur were known as \"maraschino cherries\".<ref name=blech>{{cite book|last=Blech|first=Zushe Yosef|title=Kosher Food Production|year=2009|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=0-8138-2093-6|pages=266}}</ref> This had been a local means of preserving the fruit in [[Dalmatia]].<ref name=\"Blech 2009\"/>\n\nIn the 19th century, these became popular in the rest of Europe, but the supply in Dalmatia was too small for the whole continent, so they came to be seen as a delicacy for royalty and the wealthy.\n\nBecause of the relative scarcity of the Marasca, other cherries came to be preserved in various ways and sold as \"maraschino\".\n\n==United States==\nThe cherries were first introduced in the United States in the late 19th century, where they were served in fine bars and [[restaurant]]s. Because they were scarce and expensive, by the turn of the century American producers were experimenting with other processes for preserving cherries, with flavors such as [[almond extract]] and substitute fruit like [[Royal Ann cherry|Queen Anne cherries]]. Among these, alcohol was already becoming less common.\n\nIn response, the [[USDA]] in 1912 defined \"maraschino cherries\" as \"Marasca cherries preserved in maraschino\" under the authority of the [[Food and Drugs Act of 1906]]. The artificially-colored and sweetened Royal Anne variety were required to be called \"Imitation Maraschino Cherries\" instead.<ref name=\"FDA CPG\">{{cite web|author=U.S. FDA | date=1980-01-10 |url=https://www.fda.gov/ICECI/ComplianceManuals/CompliancePolicyGuidanceManual/ucm074535.htm |title=Sec. 550.550 Maraschino Cherries |work= CPG 7110.11 |accessdate=2006-05-16 }}</ref> Food Inspection Decision 141 defined Marasca cherries and maraschino themselves.<ref>{{cite journal |author=USDA |title=Food Inspection Decision 141. The Labeling of Maraschino and Maraschino Cherries |journal=California State Board of Health Monthly Bulletin |volume=8 |issue=1 |date=July 1812 |pages=11\u201312 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=krTHhGoGJuEC&pg=RA1-PA11 |publisher=State Board of Health}}</ref> It was signed on Feb. 17, 1912.<ref name=\"Wiley\">{{cite book |title=The History of a Crime Against the Food Law |authorlink=Harvey W. Wiley |author=Wiley, Harvey W. |year=1976 |publisher=Ayer |chapter=Chapter III: Rules and Regulations |chapterurl=http://www.soilandhealth.org/03sov/0303critic/030305wylie/030305ch3.html |url=http://www.soilandhealth.org/03sov/0303critic/030305wylie/030305toc.html |accessdate=2007-07-04}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Prohibition in the United States]] as of 1920, the decreasingly popular alcoholic variety was illegal as well. [[Ernest H. Wiegand]], a professor of [[horticulture]] at [[Oregon State University]] (OSU), developed the modern method of manufacturing maraschino cherries using a brine solution rather than alcohol.<ref name=who/><ref>{{Oregon Encyclopedia|maraschino_cherries|author=Verzemnieks, Inara}}</ref> Accordingly, most modern maraschino cherries have only a historical connection with maraschino liqueur.\n\nAccording to Bob Cain, Cliff Samuels, and Hoya Yang, who worked with Wiegand at OSU, Prohibition had nothing to do with Wiegand's research: his intention was to develop a better brining process for cherries that would not soften them. When Wiegand began his research, there were several ways to preserve maraschino cherries without alcohol, long before Prohibition went into effect. Wiegand took a process that people had their own recipes for\u2014\"and who knows what they were putting in there\" (frequently not alcohol)\u2014and turned it into a science, something replicable.<ref>{{cite news|title=The fruit that made Oregon famous |first=Inara |last=Verzemnieks |date=2006-02-12 |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/oregoniantest/2007/04/the_fruit_that_made_oregon_fam.html |accessdate=2007-07-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930040753/http://blog.oregonlive.com/oregoniantest/2007/04/the_fruit_that_made_oregon_fam.html |archivedate=30 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhen Wiegand began his research, [[sodium metabisulfite]] was being used to preserve maraschino cherries. Some accounts indicate that this preservation method was being used long before Prohibition. Some manufacturers used maraschino or imitation liqueurs to flavor the cherries, but newspaper stories from the early part of the century suggest that many manufacturers stopped using alcohol and artificial dyes before Prohibition.\n\nAfter [[Repeal of Prohibition|Prohibition was repealed]], lobbying by the non-alcoholic preserved cherry industry encouraged the [[Food and Drug Administration]] to revise federal policy toward canned cherries. It held a hearing in April 1939 to establish a new [[standard of identity]]. Since 1940, \"maraschino cherries\" have been defined as \"cherries which have been dyed red, impregnated with sugar, and packed in a sugar syrup flavored with [[Almond#Sweet and bitter almonds|oil of bitter almonds]] or a similar flavor.\"<ref name=\"FDA CPG\" />\n\nFD&C Red Number 1 and 4, and FD&C Yellow Number 1 through 4 were removed from the approved list in 1960. The ban on [[FD&C Red No. 4|Red Number 4]] was lifted in 1965 to allow the coloring of maraschino cherries, which by then were considered mainly decorative and not a foodstuff.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pavia|first=Donald L.|year=2005|title=Introduction to Organic Laboratory Techniques: A Small Scale Approach|edition=2nd}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=March 2020}}  In 1975, [[William F. Randolph]] of the [[FDA]] ruled that if an \"artificial bitter almond flavor or any synthetic flavor is used, the product must be labeled artificial or artificially flavored.\"<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=U.S. Sets Up Limits for Processors of Maraschino Cherries |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F04E4D8123CE034BC4A53DFB266838E669EDE |quote=There are limits beyond which the processors of maraschino cherries may not go, the United States Food and Drug Administration has decided. ... |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=April 2, 1975 |accessdate=2015-02-20 }}</ref>  The following year, the ban on Red No. 4 was reinstated. \n\nAs of 2010, modern American Maraschino cherries typically use [[FD&C Red 40]] as a colorant.<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=The Mystery of the Red Bees of Red Hook |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/30/nyregion/30bigcity.html |quote=... Red Dye No. 40, the same dye used in the maraschino cherry juice. |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=November 29, 2010 |accessdate=2015-02-20 }}</ref>\n\n==Pairing==\nMaraschino cherries are associated with ice cream sundaes and ice cream desserts.<ref>{{cite book | title=Ice Cream Trade Journal | publisher=Cutler-Williams Company | issue=v. 5 | year=1909 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0TJPAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA7-PA30 | access-date=August 26, 2018 | page=30}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* A similar process produces [[glac\u00e9 fruit]]\n* [[Amarena cherry|Amarena cherries]]\n* [[List of cherry dishes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite magazine |title=The Maraschino Cherry |magazine=The International Confectioner| volume=23 | year=1914 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IwRQAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA43 | access-date=August 25, 2018 | pages=43-44}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Maraschino cherries}}\n\n{{Bartend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maraschino Cherry}}\n[[Category:Agriculture in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Cherry dishes]]\n[[Category:Cocktail garnishes]]\n[[Category:Food preservation]]\n[[Category:Oregon State University]]\n", "text_old": "{{use dmy dates |date=February 2016}}\n{{About|the fruit|the film by Radley Metzger|Maraschino Cherry (film)}}\n[[File:Maraschino cherries.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Maraschino cherries]]\n[[File:Real maraschino cherries.jpg|thumb|Two [[Girolamo Luxardo|Luxardo]]-brand maraschino cherries are shown impaled on a cocktail pick, atop a jar of more of the same cherries in syrup. Some high-end brands of maraschino cherries such as those pictured omit the ubiquitous bright red dye, opting for a darker colored product.]]\n[[File:Whiskey_sour_in_coupe_glass_with_garnishes.jpg|thumb|A [[whiskey sour]] garnished with two [[Girolamo Luxardo|Luxardo]]-brand maraschino cherries in addition to other garnishes.]]\n[[File:Tequila Sunrise glass.jpg|thumb|A [[Tequila Sunrise (cocktail)|Tequila Sunrise]] cocktail [[Garnish (food)|garnished]] with a maraschino cherry]]\n[[File:Macromaraschino.jpg|thumb|Close-up, maraschino cherry]]\nA '''maraschino cherry''' ({{IPAc-en|m|\u00e6r|\u0259|\u02c8|s|k|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}} {{respell|marr-\u0259|SKEE|noh}} or {{IPAc-en|m|\u00e6r|\u0259|\u02c8|\u0283|i\u02d0|n|o\u028a}} {{respell|marr-\u0259|SHEE|noh}}) is a preserved, sweetened [[cherry]], typically made from light-colored sweet cherries such as the [[Royal Ann cherry|Royal Ann]],<ref>{{cite book | last=Murray | first=M.T. | last2=Pizzorno | first2=J. | last3=Pizzorno | first3=L. | title=The Encyclopedia of Healing Foods | publisher=Atria Books | year=2010 | isbn=978-1-4391-0344-9 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UKtAMVUT57EC&pg=PA264 | access-date=August 25, 2018 | page=264}}</ref> [[Rainier cherry|Rainier]], or Gold varieties. In their modern form, the cherries are first preserved in a [[brine]] solution usually containing [[sulfur dioxide]] and [[calcium chloride]] to bleach the fruit, then soaked in a [[Suspension (chemistry)|suspension]] of [[food coloring]] (common red food dye is [[Allura Red AC|FD&C Red 40]]), [[sugar syrup]], and other components.<ref name=who>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=Who Made That Maraschino Cherry? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/21/magazine/who-made-that-maraschino-cherry.html |quote= In 1925, Wiegand discovered that adding calcium salts to the preserving brine firmed up the fruit. |newspaper=[[New York Times Magazine]] |date=September 19, 2014 |accessdate=2015-02-20 }}</ref>\n\nMaraschino cherries are an ingredient in many [[cocktail]]s, giving them the nickname \"cocktail cherries\". As a [[Garnish (food)|garnish]], they often are used to decorate [[frozen yogurt]], baked [[ham]], [[cake]]s, [[pastry]], [[parfait]]s, [[milkshake]]s, [[sundae|ice cream sundaes]], and [[ice cream soda]]s. They are an integral part of an American [[ice cream sundae]]. The term \"cherry on top\" refers to the Maraschino cherries on top of the ice cream sundae. They are frequently included in canned [[fruit cocktail]].<ref>[[USDA]]'s [http://www.ams.usda.gov/AMSv1.0/getfile?dDocName=STELPRD3105806 Grading Manual for Canned Fruit Cocktail]</ref> Sometimes the cherries, along with some of the maraschino syrup, are put into a glass of [[Coca-Cola]] to make an old-fashioned or homemade \"[[Cherry Coke]]\".\n\n==Europe==\nThe name ''maraschino'' originates from the [[Marasca cherry]] of [[Croatian cuisine|Croatian]] origin<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://whatscookingamerica.net/History/MaraschinoCherry.htm|title=The fruit that made Oregon famous! (in Maraschino Cherry History)|last=Verzemnieks|first=Inara|date=February 12, 2006|work=The Oregonian|via=What's Cooking America website|access-date=2019-02-07}}</ref> and the [[maraschino]] [[liqueur]] made from it, in which Marasca cherries were crushed and preserved after being pickled.<ref name=\"Blech 2009\">{{cite book | last=Blech | first=Z.Y. | title=Kosher Food Production | publisher=Wiley | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8138-0480-4 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=smFVSUWXTbkC&pg=PA266 | access-date=August 25, 2018 | page=266}}</ref> Whole cherries preserved in this liqueur were known as \"maraschino cherries\".<ref name=blech>{{cite book|last=Blech|first=Zushe Yosef|title=Kosher Food Production|year=2009|publisher=John Wiley and Sons|isbn=0-8138-2093-6|pages=266}}</ref> This had been a local means of preserving the fruit in [[Dalmatia]].<ref name=\"Blech 2009\"/>\n\nIn the 19th century, these became popular in the rest of Europe, but the supply in Dalmatia was too small for the whole continent, so they came to be seen as a delicacy for royalty and the wealthy.\n\nBecause of the relative scarcity of the Marasca, other cherries came to be preserved in various ways and sold as \"maraschino\".\n\n==United States==\nThe cherries were first introduced in the United States in the late 19th century, where they were served in fine bars and [[restaurant]]s. Because they were scarce and expensive, by the turn of the century American producers were experimenting with other processes for preserving cherries, with flavors such as [[almond extract]] and substitute fruit like [[Royal Ann cherry|Queen Anne cherries]]. Among these, alcohol was already becoming less common.\n\nIn response, the [[USDA]] in 1912 defined \"maraschino cherries\" as \"Marasca cherries preserved in maraschino\" under the authority of the [[Food and Drugs Act of 1906]]. The artificially-colored and sweetened Royal Anne variety were required to be called \"Imitation Maraschino Cherries\" instead.<ref name=\"FDA CPG\">{{cite web|author=U.S. FDA | date=1980-01-10 |url=https://www.fda.gov/ICECI/ComplianceManuals/CompliancePolicyGuidanceManual/ucm074535.htm |title=Sec. 550.550 Maraschino Cherries |work= CPG 7110.11 |accessdate=2006-05-16 }}</ref> Food Inspection Decision 141 defined Marasca cherries and maraschino themselves.<ref>{{cite journal |author=USDA |title=Food Inspection Decision 141. The Labeling of Maraschino and Maraschino Cherries |journal=California State Board of Health Monthly Bulletin |volume=8 |issue=1 |date=July 1812 |pages=11\u201312 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=krTHhGoGJuEC&pg=RA1-PA11 |publisher=State Board of Health}}</ref> It was signed on Feb. 17, 1912.<ref name=\"Wiley\">{{cite book |title=The History of a Crime Against the Food Law |authorlink=Harvey W. Wiley |author=Wiley, Harvey W. |year=1976 |publisher=Ayer |chapter=Chapter III: Rules and Regulations |chapterurl=http://www.soilandhealth.org/03sov/0303critic/030305wylie/030305ch3.html |url=http://www.soilandhealth.org/03sov/0303critic/030305wylie/030305toc.html |accessdate=2007-07-04}}</ref>\n\nDuring [[Prohibition in the United States]] as of 1920, the decreasingly popular alcoholic variety was illegal as well. [[Ernest H. Wiegand]], a professor of [[horticulture]] at [[Oregon State University]] (OSU), developed the modern method of manufacturing maraschino cherries using a brine solution rather than alcohol.<ref name=who/><ref>{{Oregon Encyclopedia|maraschino_cherries|author=Verzemnieks, Inara}}</ref> Accordingly, most modern maraschino cherries have only a historical connection with maraschino liqueur.\n\nAccording to Bob Cain, Cliff Samuels, and Hoya Yang, who worked with Wiegand at OSU, Prohibition had nothing to do with Wiegand's research: his intention was to develop a better brining process for cherries that would not soften them. When Wiegand began his research, there were several ways to preserve maraschino cherries without alcohol, long before Prohibition went into effect. Wiegand took a process that people had their own recipes for\u2014\"and who knows what they were putting in there\" (frequently not alcohol)\u2014and turned it into a science, something replicable.<ref>{{cite news|title=The fruit that made Oregon famous |first=Inara |last=Verzemnieks |date=2006-02-12 |newspaper=[[The Oregonian]] |url=http://blog.oregonlive.com/oregoniantest/2007/04/the_fruit_that_made_oregon_fam.html |accessdate=2007-07-04 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930040753/http://blog.oregonlive.com/oregoniantest/2007/04/the_fruit_that_made_oregon_fam.html |archivedate=30 September 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nWhen Wiegand began his research, [[sodium metabisulfite]] was being used to preserve maraschino cherries. Some accounts indicate that this preservation method was being used long before Prohibition. Some manufacturers used maraschino or imitation liqueurs to flavor the cherries, but newspaper stories from the early part of the century suggest that many manufacturers stopped using alcohol and artificial dyes before Prohibition.\n\nAfter [[Repeal of Prohibition|Prohibition was repealed]], lobbying by the non-alcoholic preserved cherry industry encouraged the [[Food and Drug Administration]] to revise federal policy toward canned cherries. It held a hearing in April 1939 to establish a new [[standard of identity]]. Since 1940, \"maraschino cherries\" have been defined as \"cherries which have been dyed red, impregnated with sugar, and packed in a sugar syrup flavored with [[Almond#Sweet and bitter almonds|oil of bitter almonds]] or a similar flavor.\"<ref name=\"FDA CPG\" />\n\nFD&C Red Number 1 and 4, and FD&C Yellow Number 1 through 4 were removed from the approved list in 1960. The ban on [[FD&C Red No. 4|Red Number 4]] was lifted in 1965 to allow the coloring of maraschino cherries, which by then were considered mainly decorative and not a foodstuff.<ref>{{cite book |last=Pavia|first=Donald L.|year=2005|title=Introduction to Organic Laboratory Techniques: A Small Scale Approach|edition=2nd}}</ref>{{full citation needed|date=March 2020}}  In 1975, [[William F. Randolph]] of the [[FDA]] ruled that if an \"artificial bitter almond flavor or any synthetic flavor is used, the product must be labeled artificial or artificially flavored.\"<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=U.S. Sets Up Limits for Processors of Maraschino Cherries |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F04E4D8123CE034BC4A53DFB266838E669EDE |quote=There are limits beyond which the processors of maraschino cherries may not go, the United States Food and Drug Administration has decided. ... |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=April 2, 1975 |accessdate=2015-02-20 }}</ref>  The following year, the ban on Red No. 4 was reinstated. \n\nAs of 2010, modern American Maraschino cherries typically use [[FD&C Red 40]] as a colorant.<ref>{{cite news |author= |coauthors= |title=The Mystery of the Red Bees of Red Hook |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/30/nyregion/30bigcity.html |quote=... Red Dye No. 40, the same dye used in the maraschino cherry juice. |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=November 29, 2010 |accessdate=2015-02-20 }}</ref>\n\n==Pairing==\nMaraschino cherries are associated with ice cream sundaes and ice cream desserts.<ref>{{cite book | title=Ice Cream Trade Journal | publisher=Cutler-Williams Company | issue=v. 5 | year=1909 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0TJPAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA7-PA30 | access-date=August 26, 2018 | page=30}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Food}}\n* A similar process produces [[glac\u00e9 fruit]]\n* [[Amarena cherry|Amarena cherries]]\n* [[List of cherry dishes]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite magazine |title=The Maraschino Cherry |magazine=The International Confectioner| volume=23 | year=1914 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IwRQAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA2-PA43 | access-date=August 25, 2018 | pages=43-44}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category inline|Maraschino cherries}}\n\n{{Bartend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Maraschino Cherry}}\n[[Category:Agriculture in Oregon]]\n[[Category:Cherry dishes]]\n[[Category:Cocktail garnishes]]\n[[Category:Food preservation]]\n[[Category:Oregon State University]]\n", "name_user": "Ilikefood", "label": "safe", "comment": "removing unnecessary comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maraschino_cherry"}
{"title_page": "Ice hockey in the United States", "text_new": "{{Infobox sport overview\n| boxwidth      = 250\n| title         = Ice hockey in the United States\n| image         = Interior_of_little_Caesars_arena_panorama.jpg\n|caption        = [[Little Caesars Arena]]\n| imagesize     = 240px\n| image_alt     = \n| union         = [[USA Hockey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nhl/story/_/id/9418183/usa-hockey-encourages-kids-nhl-dreams-play-other-sports-espn-magazine |title=USA Hockey encourages kids with NHL dreams to play other sports - ESPN The Magazine |website=Espn.co.uk |date=2013-06-26 |accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Beth|last=Maiman |url=https://www.si.com/nhl/2016/06/28/nhl-hockey-is-for-everyone-inner-city-youth-programs |title=NHL inner city youth hockey programs continue to grow |website=Sports Illustrated |date=22 March 2016 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= What A Mostly Black Hockey Club For Kids Tells Us About The Sport's Future|publisher= Huffington Post|date=22 January 2016|first=Travis|last=Waldron|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-hockey-fort-dupont_us_5679c78be4b0b958f6588057|accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| country       = United States \n| sport         = ice hockey\n| noncountry    = <!-- other country this country represents -->\n| teamlabel1    = <!-- overrides the \"National team\" label with custom label -->\n| nationalteam  = [[United States men's national ice hockey team|Men's national team]] <br> [[United States women's national ice hockey team|Women's national team]]\n| teamlabel2    = <!-- overrides the \"Representative team\" label with customer label -->\n| repteam       = <!-- overrides the representative team link, requires full wikitext syntax -->\n| nickname      = <!-- nicknames -->\n| first         = 1893\n| registered    =\n| clubs         = \n| national_list =  [[National Hockey League]]\n| club_list     =  [[Stanley Cup]]\n| intl_list     = [[IIHF World Championships]] <br /> [[Ice hockey at the Olympics|Winter Olympics]] <br /> [[World Cup of Hockey|World Cup]] \n| match         = \n| league        = \n}}\n[[Ice hockey]], usually referred to in the U.S. simply as \"hockey\", is a popular sport in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.macleans.ca/society/the-united-states-of-hockey/|title=Is hockey becoming America's game?|work=Maclean's|date=20 February 2012|first=Charlie|last=Gillis|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Campbell |first=Ken |url=http://www.thehockeynews.com/news/article/hockey-ranks-6th-in-popularity-survey-harris-poll |title=Hockey ranks 6th in popularity survey: Harris Poll |work=The Hockey News |date=27 January 2014 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSix-O4CmvMC&pg=PA1983 |title=International Sports Law and Business |volume=Volume 3|first1=Aaron N.|last1=Wise |first2=Bruce S.|last2=Meyer |page=1983 |publisher=Kluwer Law International|year=1997|isbn=90-41106022|accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref> Hockey in the U.S. began in 1894 when the first artificial ice rink was built in Baltimore, Maryland. Now hockey is most popular in regions of the U.S. with cold winter climates, such as the northeast and the upper Midwest.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/26/sports/hockey/a-brawl-is-a-blow-to-the-nhls-positive-buzz-outdoors.html|title=A Blow to the N.H.L.'s Positive Buzz|first1=Jeff Z.|last1=Klein|first2=Stu|last2=Hackel|date=25 January 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref> However, since the 1990s, ice hockey has become increasingly popular in the [[Sun Belt]] due in large part to the expansion of the [[National Hockey League]] to the southeast and southwest U.S., coupled with the mass relocation of many residents from northern cities with strong hockey support to these Sun Belt locations.<ref name=\"yahoo.com\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/california-hockey-knows-how-to-party-053314118.html|title=California puck love: Hockey popularity surging in the Golden State|website=Puck Daddy (Yahoo Sport)|first=Josh|last=Cooper|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-kings-ducks-lifestyle-20140503-story.html|title=The ice is greener in Southern California hockey|first=Helene|last=Elliott|date=2 May 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/kings/la-sp-kings-sharks-elliott-20150222-column.html|title=California has warmed to hockey, and vice versa; Kings, Ducks helped|first=Helene|last=Elliott|date=21 February 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/leigh-steinberg/la-kings_b_1582495.html|title=Will Hockey Ever Be Popular in California?|first1=Leigh|last1=Steinberg|work=The Huffington Post|date=8 June 2012|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/news/sharks-ducks-kings-turning-california-into-hockey-central/|title=Sharks, Ducks, Kings turning California into hockey central|first=Chris|last=Peters|date=3 December 2013|work=CBS Sports|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History of ice hockey in the United States==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2016}}\nThe contemporary sport of ice hockey was developed in Canada, most notably in Montreal, Quebec, where the first indoor hockey game was played on March 3, 1875. Some characteristics of that game, such as the length of the ice rink and the use of a puck, have been retained to this day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/may/28/ice-hockey-not-made-in-canada-identity|title=Ice hockey not invented in Canada? That's cold, man|date=28 May 2014|first=Matthew|last=Hays|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC&pg=RA2-PA271|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|editor1-first=John|editor1-last=Nauright|editor2-first=Charles|editor2-last=Parrish|page=271|year=2012|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|publisher=ABC-CLIO}}</ref> The game soon spread to United States.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DMOzCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA42 |title=A Brief History Of International Ice Hockey |first=Garry |last=Glave |page=42 |year=2015 |publisher=ShieldCrest Publishing |isbn=978-1-911090-10-6}}</ref> It was brought overseas from Canadian immigrants. They would play this stick and ball game on frozen ponds and lakes in the winters. The first known recorded game of ice hockey was played in the United States at [[Yale University]] and [[Johns Hopkins University]] in 1893.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdV_JV1fbZMC&pg=PA215&dq=hockey+baltimore&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=hockey%20baltimore&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Ethnicity and Sports in the United States|first1=George B.|last1=Kirsch|first2=Othello|last2=Harris|first3=Claire Elaine|last3=Nolte|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894, the first artificial ice rink was built in [[Maryland]]. The rink was called the [[North Avenue Ice Palace]], which was located in Baltimore, Maryland. A few years later, in 1896, the first ice hockey league in the United States was formed called The U.S. Amateur Hockey League. It was founded in New York City around the same time as the second artificial ice rink was opened in New York, New York, called the [[St. Nicholas Rink|St. Nicholas Arena]]. The U.S. Amateur Hockey League then became a member of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] in 1904. There were five teams from the United States and Ontario that formed the International Ice Hockey Federation. This league only lasted three seasons but it was the first professional ice hockey league that the United States participated in.{{fact|date=March 2018}}\n\nMeanwhile, teams in western Canada formed the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]] in 1911. This league created new designs and rules that helped ice hockey evolve into the game it is today. Some of these new innovations that were created were blue lines that were painted under the ice which divided the ice into three sections, goaltenders are allowed to fall and slide on the ice to help prevent the other team from scoring a goal, forward passing is permitted in the neutral zone, and the game was split into three periods of 20 minutes. In 1912, the game changed again reducing the number of on-ice players to six players from the previous seven.{{fact|date=March 2018}}\n\n==National Hockey League==\n{{Main article|History of the National Hockey League}}\nThe [[National Hockey League|NHL]] is the major professional hockey league in North America, with 24 U.S.-based teams and 7 Canadian-based teams competing for the [[Stanley Cup]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n3Xn7jMx1RYC&pg=PA912 |title=The American Midwest: An Interpretive Encyclopedia |editor1-first=Andrew R. L. |editor1-last=Cayton |editor2-first=Richard |editor2-last=Sisson |editor3-first=Chris |editor3-last=Zache |page=912 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-253-34886-9 |accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref> While NHL stars are still not as readily familiar to the general American public as are stars of the NFL, MLB, and the NBA, average attendance for NHL games in the U.S. has surpassed average NBA attendance in recent seasons,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://detroit.cbslocal.com/2014/01/09/why-is-hockey-more-popular-than-basketball-in-detroit-and-across-the-country/ |title=Why Is Hockey More Popular Than Basketball \u2013 In Detroit And Across The Country? |first=Ashley|last=Dunkak|date=9 January 2014|work=CBS Detroit|accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Ryan|last=Glasspiegel |url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2014/01/08/nhl-versus-nba-attendance |title=The NHL is Reportedly Selling Out More Markets Than the NBA This Season |work=Sports Illustrated |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref> buoyed in part by the [[NHL Winter Classic]] being played in large outdoor stadiums.<ref>{{cite news|last=Berr |first=Jonathan |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/how-the-nhl-got-on-a-winning-streak/ |title=How the NHL got on a scoring streak |work=[[CBS News]] |date=10 November 2014 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.hookedonhockeymagazine.com/hockey-continues-to-grow-in-the-united-states/ |title=Hockey Continues to Grow in the United States |journal=Hooked on Hockey Magazine |first=Igor |last=Burdetskiy |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=Brough |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/hockey/nhl-popularity-rising-heres-the-proof |title=NHL Popularity Rising \u2013 Here's the Proof |website=The Province |date=22 April 2008 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924, the [[Boston Bruins]] were the first American team to join the [[National Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqy8U_d1LEcC&pg=PA29&dq=boston+bruins+original+six&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGxaOr_vPQAhWIKsAKHcTVBeMQ6AEIXDAG#v=onepage&q=boston%20bruins%20original%20six&f=false |title=The Legendary Game - Ultimate Hockey Trivia |author=Tom King |page=29 |website=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref> During that season, the first NHL game was played in the United States where the Boston Bruins defeated the [[Montreal Maroons]] 2\u20131. That same season, the NHL increased the season schedule from 24 games to 30 games.  Three more American teams the [[New York Rangers]], [[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]] and [[Detroit Cougars (NHL)|Detroit Cougars]], joined the NHL in the year 1926. That same year, the [[Western Canada Hockey League|Western Hockey League]] fell apart and sold most of its players to the new NHL teams. This makes the NHL the top hockey league in North America. In 1942, the [[Brooklyn Americans]] withdrew from the NHL. This left the Canadiens, Maple Leafs, Red Wings, Bruins, Rangers, and Black Hawks as the only teams left in the NHL for the next 25 years. Those six teams are now called \"[[the Original Six]].\"\n\n[[New Brunswick]]-born skater [[Willie O'Ree]] became the [[Black players in ice hockey|first black ice hockey player in the NHL]] for the [[Boston Bruins]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Harry|last=Thompson |url=http://www.usahockeymagazine.com/article/2013-11/equal-ice-diversity-hockey |title=Equal Ice: Diversity in Hockey |journal=USA Hockey Magazine |date=November 2013 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref> while [[Val James]] was the first African American player to compete in the NHL for the [[Buffalo Sabres]] and [[Toronto Maple Leafs]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/04/sports/hockey/val-james-first-us-born-black-player-in-nhl-publishes-autobiography.html|title=N.H.L. Trailblazer Finds Forgiveness in the Tip of a Pen|first=Pat|last=Borzi|date=3 February 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-10-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 the [[World Hockey Association]] formed of 12 teams from Canada and the United States intended to rival the NHL but ultimately failed and many of the teams merged with the NHL.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VUT0v_BSkFoC&pg=PA2&dq=world+hockey+association&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTm8fH_vPQAhUJM8AKHTICBPEQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=world%20hockey%20association&f=false |title=The Complete Historical and Statistical Reference to the World Hockey ... |author=Scott Surgent |page=2 |website=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==Stanley Cup==\nThe [[Stanley Cup]] is the oldest trophy in North American sports. [[Lord Stanley of Preston]] was appointed by [[Queen Victoria]] to be the Governor General of Canada on June 11, 1888. While governor, Ice hockey was still just forming in Canada. He first got to see the game of hockey played at Montreal's 1889 Winter Carnival. During the carnival he watched the Montreal Victorias play the Montreal Hockey Club. Since then he and his family became very involved in the game of ice hockey. His two sons, Arthur and Algernon, convinced their father to donate a trophy that would be considered to be a visible sign of the ice hockey championship. This trophy was a silver bowl inlaid with gold.  The trophy was first presented in 1893 and was called the Dominion Hockey Challenge Cup. The name of the trophy was later changed to the famous name, The Stanley Cup.\n\nIn 1914 the [[Portland Rosebuds (ice hockey)|Portland Rosebuds]], an American-based team, joined the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]]. After that, the trustees of the Stanley Cup made a statement that the Stanley Cup was no longer for the best team in Canada, but now the best team in the whole world. The Rosebuds became the first American team to compete in the Stanley Cup Finals two years later. In the year 1917, the team [[Seattle Metropolitans]] was the first American team to win the Stanley Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/other-sports/when-seattle-was-hockeytown-usa/|title=When Seattle was Hockeytown USA|date=2 March 2013|publisher=SB Nation|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> Once that season was over, the National Hockey Association was changed into the NHL or the [[National Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014/8/5/5969737/seattle-metropolitans-history-stanley-cup-hockey-pcha-nhl|title=Remembering America's first Stanley Cup champion|first=Adam|last=Gretz|date=5 August 2014|publisher=[[Seattle Times]]|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Minor leagues==\n\nMinor league professional hockey leagues in the U.S. include the [[American Hockey League]] and the [[ECHL]]. Additionally, nine U.S.-based teams compete in the three member leagues of the [[Canadian Hockey League]].\n[[USA Hockey]] is the official governing body for amateur hockey in the U.S. The [[United States Hockey Hall of Fame]] is located in [[Eveleth, Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f9YJSX7JQAoC&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&source=bl&ots=jTPF_giLq1&sig=DekDXtoFh7dB1QWTLBM3oTcPHus&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFxa_HhvDQAhXNFsAKHXAOBYY4MhDoAQggMAE#v=onepage&q=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&f=false|title=Boating Life|publisher=|accessdate=13 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vYhlFmPSNgEC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&source=bl&ots=JZVC6ur2lr&sig=yBc6bFHVblRJj-_uhapGOXdxxCA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiK1uDjhvDQAhVFJcAKHfHCDWU4HhDoAQgeMAE#v=onepage&q=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&f=false|title=Hockey in Providence|first=Jim|last=Mancuso|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|accessdate=13 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Ice hockey structure==\n\n{{Main article|United States ice hockey structure}}\n\nThe '''United States ice hockey structure''' includes elements from traditional American scholastic [[high school]] and [[college]] athletics, affiliated and independent [[minor league]]s, and the unique \"[[Junior ice hockey#Major junior|Major Junior]]\" leagues. The [[hierarchy]] of the ice hockey league system forms a pyramid with a large number of regional minor and development leagues making up the base of the pyramid and a linear progression through the professional minor leagues leading to the Nation Hockey League at the top of the pyramid.\n\n==Amateur ice hockey==\n[[College ice hockey|College hockey]] has a regional following in the northeastern and upper midwestern United States. It is increasingly being used to develop players for the NHL and other professional leagues (the U.S. has junior leagues, the [[United States Hockey League]] and [[North American Hockey League]], but they are more restricted to protect junior players' college eligibility). The [[Frozen Four]] is college hockey's national championship.\n\nSummer [[senior ice hockey]] is increasing in popularity in the 21st century, with [[Edina, Minnesota]]'s Da Beauty League and [[Buffalo, New York]]'s Fattey Hockey League both drawing NHL players who use the leagues to stay in shape during the offseason.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/466460/2018/08/09/heres-how-dahlin-mittelstadt-ended-up-playing-buffalo-summer-league-hockey/|first=Joe|last=Yerdon|title=Here\u2019s how Dahlin, Mittelstadt ended up playing in Buffalo\u2019s Fattey Hockey League|work=[[The Athletic]]|date=August 10, 2018|accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Da Beauty League, established in 2016, is considered the nation's premier summer ice hockey league and benefits from corporate sponsorship from the Minnesota business community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nhl/2018/07/12/da-beauty-league-nick-bjugstad-brock-boeser-summer-hockey|title=NHLer-Laden Da Beauty League Returns for Third Season of Summer Hockey\n|first=Michael|last=Blinn|work=[[SI.com]]|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Olympics==\n{{main article|Ice hockey at the Olympic Games}}\n[[Image:1936 US Olympic Ice Hockey Team.jpg|right|thumb|The bronze medal winning [[United States at the 1936 Winter Olympics|1936 American Olympic team]].]]\nA hockey tournament debuted in the Summer Olympics in 1920 and would later also be recognized as the first World Ice Hockey Championship. Canada took the gold medal, with the United States getting the silver. The Canadians went on to claim three consecutive golds after the sport was permanently transferred to the newly established Winter Olympics in 1924. In 1936, their streak was ended by the British team that went on to beat the Canadians and tie the Americans, claiming the gold. Canada reclaimed gold in 1948 and defended it in 1952. However, the Soviet Union ended Canadian dominance in 1956, winning gold, and went on to win all Olympic tournaments until 1992 with 1960 and 1980, when the Americans were victorious, being lone exceptions. Much of this has to do with the fact that, unlike the Soviets, the Canadians were unable to use their best players. After 1992, four nations won gold medals: Canada (7th, 8th, and 9th titles), Sweden (1st and 2nd title), Czech Republic (1st title), and, the most recent champions, Russia (9th title). From 1998 to 2014, NHL players participated in the Olympics. In 1994 and 2018, players from all professional leagues except the NHL and AHL competed. Prior to 1947 there was no nationally recognized national governing body for ice hockey in the United States. The Amateur Hockey Association of the United States or AHAUS, which later became [[USA Hockey]], was created that year and has remained the governing body of ice hockey in the United States since then. The [[United States men's national ice hockey team|United States men's team]] has won two gold medals ([[Ice hockey at the 1960 Winter Olympics|1960]], [[Ice hockey at the 1980 Winter Olympics|1980]]), eight silver medals ([[Ice hockey at the 1920 Winter Olympics|1920]], [[Ice hockey at the 1924 Winter Olympics|1924]], [[Ice hockey at the 1932 Winter Olympics|1932]], [[Ice hockey at the 1952 Winter Olympics|1952]], [[Ice hockey at the 1956 Winter Olympics|1956]], [[Ice hockey at the 1972 Winter Olympics|1972]], [[Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002]], [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010]]) and one bronze medal ([[Ice hockey at the 1936 Winter Olympics|1936]]). The 1980 gold medal victory is still remembered as one of the greatest upsets in sporting history, with team USA beating four-time defending champions the USSR in the medal round. The [[United States women's national ice hockey team|women's team]] has won two gold medals ([[Ice hockey at the 1998 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|1998]], [[Ice hockey at the 2018 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2018]]), three silver medals ([[Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2002]], [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2010]], [[Ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics|2014]]), and one bronze medal ([[Ice hockey at the 2006 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2006]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdV_JV1fbZMC&pg=PA219&lpg=PA219&dq=Race%20and%20Ethnicity%20in%20the%20NHL&source=bl&ots=fiJmB3dwQJ&sig=LYuNSG2GvZD-I06xrvl7-0v8LUY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH_76T_PLQAhUMLcAKHQM6Cys4ChDoAQgmMAI#v=snippet&q=ahaus&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Ethnicity and Sports in the United States|first1=George B.|last1=Kirsch|first2=Othello|last2=Harris|first3=Claire Elaine|last3=Nolte|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/olympics/story/_/id/12360850/miracle-ice-1980-us-olympic-hockey-team-reunites-lake-placid|title=All living 'Miracle' members reunite|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=22 February 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/hockey/u-s-shocks-russians-4-3-article-1.2014732|title=Miracle on Ice! Mike Eruzione's goal, Jim Craig's heroics lead U.S. to stunning upset over the Russians in Lake Placid, 4\u20133|first=Lawrie|last=Mifflin|date=23 February 1980|work= New York Daily News|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cbssports1980\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/news/american-hockey-has-come-a-long-way-since-1980s-miraculous-gold/|title=American hockey has come a long way since 1980's miraculous gold|first=Chris|last=Peters|date=24 February 2015|work=CBS Sports|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/longterm/olympics1998/history/memories/80-hock.htm|title=U.S. Shocks Soviets in Ice Hockey, 4\u20133|publisher=Washington Post|first=Leonard|last=Shapiro|date=23 February 1980|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/big/0222.html |title=U.S. Defeats Soviet Squad In Olympic Hockey by 4\u20133 |first=Gerald|last=Eskenazi|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=23 February 1980 |accessdate=2016-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/9418183/usa-hockey-encourages-kids-nhl-dreams-play-other-sports-espn-magazine|title=Miracle on ice|first=Tom|last=Farrey|date=26 June 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.si.com/nhl/2015/02/23/1980-usa-olympic-hockey-team-miracle-on-ice-35th-reunion-at-lake-placid|title=Poignant reunion for the Miracle on Ice team at Lake Placid|first=Stefanie|last=Gordon|date=23 February 2015|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Women's ice hockey==\n{{main article|History of women's ice hockey in the United States}}\nWomen's ice hockey is less popular.<ref>{{cite news|first=Seth|last=Berkman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/05/sports/hockey/obstacles-for-global-talent-in-national-womens-hockey-league.html |title=Obstacles for Global Talent in National Women's Hockey League |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=4 March 2016 |accessdate=2016-10-09}}</ref> The [[National Women's Hockey League]], founded in 2015, is the first in the country to pay its players, and featured four teams from the Northeast.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/01/21/463073576/womens-hockey-takes-stage-as-new-pro-sports-league |title=Women's Hockey Takes Stage As New Pro Sports League |work=[[NPR]] |date=21 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-10-09}}</ref> Through partnerships with NHL teams, the league survived and expanded to five teams for its fourth season in 2018, adding the [[Minnesota Whitecaps]] (a long-established independent team) that year. Four of the league's five teams are owned and operated by the league itself; the lone exception is the Whitecaps. In 2019, a player strike led to two of the NHL partnerships being severed and one of the teams, the [[Buffalo Beauts]], being placed into legal limbo after [[Pegula Sports and Entertainment]] (which had purchased the team in 2017) surrendered the NWHL franchise back to the league but not the intellectual property or arena lease. The player strike was brought on by a disconnect between the demands of the NWHL's players to be paid and treated more professionally than they have been, and the NWHL's inability to enter into the agreements necessary for those demands to be met.\n\n==Television coverage==\n{{main article|History of the National Hockey League on United States television}}\n{{Expand section|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn 1957, [[NHL on CBS|CBS]] was the first U.S. television network to carry NHL games.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1957/10/28/605545/the-hockey-rebellion\n|title=The Hockey Rebellion|date=October 28, 1957|first=Dan|last=Parker|journal=Sports Illustrated}}</ref> Later, the television network NBC also started carrying some NHL games. Both television networks held rights to show NHL games at times, but neither television network showed a full NHL schedule. They only carried select games from the Stanley Cup Finals. From the year 1971 to the year 1995 no United States television network had exclusive coverage of the NHL games. The USA television network started carrying 35 regular-season games and played the full schedule of the playoff games from the year 1981 to 1985.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1983/01/24/625121/getting-down-to-business |title=Getting Down To Business |date=January 24, 1983 |first=William |last=Taaffe |journal=Sports Illustrated |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427143048/http://www.si.com/vault/1983/01/24/625121/getting-down-to-business |archivedate=April 27, 2015 }}</ref> [[ESPN National Hockey Night|ESPN]] replaced the USA network in 1985 and then [[SportsChannel America|\nSports Channel]] replaced ESPN in 1989. ESPN came back and later took over the National Hockey Contract in 1993. The [[NHL on Fox|Fox network]] joined ESPN in the year 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-10/sports/sp-36827_1_cable-contract |title=NHL Agrees on $155-Million Deal With Fox - latimes |website=Articles.latimes.com |date=1994-09-10 |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/10/sports/hockey-fox-outbids-cbs-for-nhl-games.html |title=HOCKEY - Fox Outbids CBS for N.H.L. Games |website=NYTimes.com |date=1994-09-10 |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref> NBC and sister network [[NBCSN]] have held exclusive national rights to the NHL since 2005.\n\n==Pop culture==\n{{main article|Ice hockey in popular culture}}\n{{Expand section|date=October 2016}}\nMovies such as ''[[Miracle (2004 film)|Miracle]]'', ''[[The Mighty Ducks]]'', ''[[Youngblood (1986 film)|Youngblood]]'', and ''[[Soul on Ice (film)|Soul on Ice]]'' have become part of American culture regarding hockey.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://time.com/mighty-ducks/ |title=Quack, Quack, Quack: An Oral History of the ''Mighty Ducks'' Trilogy |first=Eric|last=Dodds|journal=Time |date=9 June 2014 |accessdate=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mWCkYfx6ydA |title=Top 10 Hockey Movies |publisher=[[Watchmojo]] |date=8 June 2015 |accessdate=2016-10-21}}</ref>\n\n==Fanbase==\n\nTraditionally, ice hockey has been played predominantly by [[White American|Caucasians]] in the United States and attended by white Americans and the [[Sports fan|fans]] are the most affluent of the 4 major team sports watched in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://psmag.com/why-the-ice-is-white-4afcd6bfd47a#.o7h8jhtjg |title=Why the Ice Is White |first=Wes |last=Judd| website=[[Pacific Standard]] |date=19 June 2015 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/christinasettimi/2015/11/24/the-nhls-least-engaged-fans/|title=The NHL's Least Engaged Fans|first=Christina|last=Settimi|date=24 November 2015|website=Forbes|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2014/02/which-sports-have-the-whitest-richest-oldest-fans/283626/|title=Which Sports Have the Whitest/Richest/Oldest Fans?|first=Derek|last=Thompson|date=10 February 2014|journal=The Atlantic|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/nhl-least-diverse-most-advertiser-friendly-tv-audience-194010102--nhl.html|title=NHL has least diverse, but most advertiser friendly, TV audience|first=Greg|last=Wyshynski|date=27 January 2014|website=Puck Daddy (Yahoo Sport)|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIce hockey is traditionally popular in [[Sports in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]], [[Sports in Michigan|Michigan]], and [[Sports in Minnesota|Minnesota]] within the United States. Minnesota is known as the hockey capital of the USA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://slapshot.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/where-hockey-is-growing-state-by-state/|title=Where Hockey is Growing, State by State|first=Jeff Z.|last=Klein|date=20 February 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/643555-the-state-of-hockey-ranking-the-top-10-hockey-states-in-america|title=The State of Hockey: Ranking the Top 10 Hockey States in America|first=Erik|last=Johnson|website=Bleacher Report|date=23 March 2011|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1\"/><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/nhl-looks-to-fix-diversity-issues-w454345|title=NHL Looks to Inner-Cities for New Generation of Diverse Players|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[NHL]] is trying to grow the sport of ice hockey by attempting to diversify the fanbase and expand from its [[Race and ethnicity in the NHL|traditional demographic]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/13/399292644/nhl-aims-to-include-more-minority-players-to-expand-fan-base|title=NHL Aims To Include More Minority Players To Expand Fan Base|publisher=NPR|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/onenacion/post/_/id/3769/hockey-eyes-hispanic-fans-for-growth |title=Hockey eyes Hispanic fans for growth |first=Martin|last=Bater|website=ESPN |date=1 May 2016|accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Yates |first=Clinton |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/im-a-black-hockey-fan-we-do-exist/2012/02/27/gIQAa7MHnR_story.html |title=I'm a black hockey fan. We do exist. |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2 March 2012 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref> A notable example is the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] has seen a significant increase in attention from ethnic minorites groups since their [[Stanley cup]] successes in the 2010s, which has resulted in the team setting up outreach programs for urban youths and low income neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/hockey/blackhawks/ct-blackhawks-fans-african-americans-spt-0612-20150611-story.html |title=African-American fans have the highest growth rate among NHL fans |first=Shannon |last=Ryan |date=11 June 2015 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/chicago/nhl/story/_/id/11707540/how-chicago-chicago-blackhawks-trying-diversify-youth-hockey |title=How Chicago, Chicago Blackhawks are trying to diversify youth hockey |website=Espn.com |date=2014-10-21 |accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Hockey interest among minorities gaining speed, NHL says|publisher= Chicago Tribune|date=|url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-06-17/news/ct-met-hockey-minorities-20130617_1_blackhawks-ray-emery-nhl-team|accessdate=2016-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nhl/story/_/id/13093287/chicago-blackhawks-see-increase-minority-hockey-fans |title=Chicago Blackhawks see increase in minority hockey fans |first=Scott|last=Powers|publisher=ESPN |date=19 June 2015 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref> The [[Washington Capitals]] also have noteworthy outreach programs for to garner interest ice hockey.<ref>{{cite news|last=El |first=Tarik |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/capitals/alex-ovechkin-has-made-ice-cool-for-areas-youth-athletes/2012/02/02/gIQASj9OzQ_story.html |title=Capitals' Alex Ovechkin has made ice hockey cool for Washington area's youth athletes |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=8 February 2012 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://cnsmaryland.org/2015/05/14/hockey-growing-in-maryland-as-washington-capitals-ovechkin-make-waves-in-nhl/ |title=Hockey Growing in Maryland as Washington Capitals, Ovechkin Make Waves In NHL|first=Brian|last=Marron|date=14 May 2015|work=Capital News Service |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/309167-hockey-in-the-hood-but-is-the-hood-in-hockey|title=\"Hockey in The Hood\": But Is The Hood in Hockey?|first=Angie|last=Lewis|publisher=Bleacher Report|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe NHL has outreach programs like \"Hockey is for Everyone\" to make ice hockey more accessible to urban youth and low income communities.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid |first=Jason |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/capitals/nhl-diversity-an-idea-that-needs-to-be-heard/2011/09/30/gIQAp2wARL_story.html |title=NHL diversity: An idea that needs to be heard  |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=6 October 2011 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/13/sports/hockey/the-nhls-diversity-program-is-beginning-to-pay-dividends.html?_r=0|title=The NHL's Diversity Program is Beginning to Pay Dividends|first=Jason|last=Diamosnov|date=13 November 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Present day==\nAs of the year 2015, there are over 2,000 ice rinks in the United States alone (United States, 2008). Also, the NHL still exists and there are now 31 teams participating in the league, with 24 in the United States and 7 in [[Canada]].  As of spring 2014, United States has won 16 medals (gold, silver, and bronze) total.\n\nThe U.S. now has more youth hockey players than all other countries, excluding Canada, combined.<ref name=Dryden>{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/features/miracle-off-ice/ |title=Miracle Off Ice |first=Ken |last=Dryden |authorlink=Ken Dryden |work=[[Grantland|Grantland.com]] |date=February 20, 2014 |accessdate=February 20, 2014}}</ref> The legacy of the Miracle on Ice is believed to be influential in popularizing the sport from a fringe sport to a mainstream sport.<ref name=\"cbssports1980\"/>\n\n==Number of registered players by state==\nNumber of registered hockey players, including male, female and junior, provided by [[USA Hockey]], as of October 2019. <ref>{{cite web |title=2018-19 Final Registration Report |url=https://cdn1.sportngin.com/attachments/document/2210-1687681/2018-19_Final_Registration_Report.pdf |publisher=[[USA Hockey]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=US States - Ranked by Population 2019 |url=http://worldpopulationreview.com/states/ |publisher=[[World Population Review]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Players\n!% of population\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Minnesota}} || 57,923 || 1.024%\n|-\n| {{Flagu|New York}} || 50,587 || 0.260%\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Massachusetts}} || 48,729 || 0.702%\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Michigan}} || 48,664 || 0.486%\n|-\n| {{Flagu|California}} || 32,696 || 0.082%\n|-\n| {{Flagu|Pennsylvania}} || 32,558 || 0.254%\n|-\n| {{Flagu