|Mississippi}} || 306 || 0.010%\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Sports in the United States}}\n{{North America topic|Ice hockey in}}\n{{NHL}}\n{{Navboxes|list=\n{{Professional Hockey}}\n{{Ice Hockey Leagues}}\n{{NHL topics}}\n{{Major Leagues}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:Ice hockey in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:History of ice hockey|United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox sport overview\n| boxwidth      = 250\n| title         = Ice hockey in the United States\n| image         = Interior_of_little_Caesars_arena_panorama.jpg\n|caption        = [[Little Caesars Arena]]\n| imagesize     = 240px\n| image_alt     = \n| union         = [[USA Hockey]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nhl/story/_/id/9418183/usa-hockey-encourages-kids-nhl-dreams-play-other-sports-espn-magazine |title=USA Hockey encourages kids with NHL dreams to play other sports - ESPN The Magazine |website=Espn.co.uk |date=2013-06-26 |accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Beth|last=Maiman |url=https://www.si.com/nhl/2016/06/28/nhl-hockey-is-for-everyone-inner-city-youth-programs |title=NHL inner city youth hockey programs continue to grow |website=Sports Illustrated |date=22 March 2016 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= What A Mostly Black Hockey Club For Kids Tells Us About The Sport's Future|publisher= Huffington Post|date=22 January 2016|first=Travis|last=Waldron|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/black-hockey-fort-dupont_us_5679c78be4b0b958f6588057|accessdate=2016-10-19}}</ref>\n| country       = United States \n| sport         = ice hockey\n| noncountry    = <!-- other country this country represents -->\n| teamlabel1    = <!-- overrides the \"National team\" label with custom label -->\n| nationalteam  = [[United States men's national ice hockey team|Men's national team]] <br> [[United States women's national ice hockey team|Women's national team]]\n| teamlabel2    = <!-- overrides the \"Representative team\" label with customer label -->\n| repteam       = <!-- overrides the representative team link, requires full wikitext syntax -->\n| nickname      = <!-- nicknames -->\n| first         = 1893\n| registered    =\n| clubs         = \n| national_list =  [[National Hockey League]]\n| club_list     =  [[Stanley Cup]]\n| intl_list     = [[IIHF World Championships]] <br /> [[Ice hockey at the Olympics|Winter Olympics]] <br /> [[World Cup of Hockey|World Cup]] \n| match         = \n| league        = \n}}\n[[Ice hockey]], usually referred to in the U.S. simply as \"hockey\", is a popular sport in the United States.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.macleans.ca/society/the-united-states-of-hockey/|title=Is hockey becoming America's game?|work=Maclean's|date=20 February 2012|first=Charlie|last=Gillis|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Campbell |first=Ken |url=http://www.thehockeynews.com/news/article/hockey-ranks-6th-in-popularity-survey-harris-poll |title=Hockey ranks 6th in popularity survey: Harris Poll |work=The Hockey News |date=27 January 2014 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oSix-O4CmvMC&pg=PA1983 |title=International Sports Law and Business |volume=Volume 3|first1=Aaron N.|last1=Wise |first2=Bruce S.|last2=Meyer |page=1983 |publisher=Kluwer Law International|year=1997|isbn=90-41106022|accessdate=2016-09-26}}</ref> Hockey in the U.S. began in 1894 when the first artificial ice rink was built in Baltimore, Maryland. Now hockey is most popular in regions of the U.S. with cold winter climates, such as the northeast and the upper Midwest.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/26/sports/hockey/a-brawl-is-a-blow-to-the-nhls-positive-buzz-outdoors.html|title=A Blow to the N.H.L.'s Positive Buzz|first1=Jeff Z.|last1=Klein|first2=Stu|last2=Hackel|date=25 January 2014|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref> However, since the 1990s, ice hockey has become increasingly popular in the [[Sun Belt]] due in large part to the expansion of the [[National Hockey League]] to the southeast and southwest U.S., coupled with the mass relocation of many residents from northern cities with strong hockey support to these Sun Belt locations.<ref name=\"yahoo.com\">{{cite web|url=https://uk.sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/california-hockey-knows-how-to-party-053314118.html|title=California puck love: Hockey popularity surging in the Golden State|website=Puck Daddy (Yahoo Sport)|first=Josh|last=Cooper|date=10 May 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-kings-ducks-lifestyle-20140503-story.html|title=The ice is greener in Southern California hockey|first=Helene|last=Elliott|date=2 May 2014|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/kings/la-sp-kings-sharks-elliott-20150222-column.html|title=California has warmed to hockey, and vice versa; Kings, Ducks helped|first=Helene|last=Elliott|date=21 February 2015|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/leigh-steinberg/la-kings_b_1582495.html|title=Will Hockey Ever Be Popular in California?|first1=Leigh|last1=Steinberg|work=The Huffington Post|date=8 June 2012|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/news/sharks-ducks-kings-turning-california-into-hockey-central/|title=Sharks, Ducks, Kings turning California into hockey central|first=Chris|last=Peters|date=3 December 2013|work=CBS Sports|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History of ice hockey in the United States==\n{{Expand section|date=October 2016}}\nThe contemporary sport of ice hockey was developed in Canada, most notably in Montreal, Quebec, where the first indoor hockey game was played on March 3, 1875. Some characteristics of that game, such as the length of the ice rink and the use of a puck, have been retained to this day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2014/may/28/ice-hockey-not-made-in-canada-identity|title=Ice hockey not invented in Canada? That's cold, man|date=28 May 2014|first=Matthew|last=Hays|work=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IkLYDgTnMxEC&pg=RA2-PA271|title=Sports Around the World: History, Culture, and Practice|editor1-first=John|editor1-last=Nauright|editor2-first=Charles|editor2-last=Parrish|page=271|year=2012|isbn=978-1-59884-300-2|publisher=ABC-CLIO}}</ref> The game soon spread to United States.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DMOzCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA42 |title=A Brief History Of International Ice Hockey |first=Garry |last=Glave |page=42 |year=2015 |publisher=ShieldCrest Publishing |isbn=978-1-911090-10-6}}</ref> It was brought overseas from Canadian immigrants. They would play this stick and ball game on frozen ponds and lakes in the winters. The first known recorded game of ice hockey was played in the United States at [[Yale University]] and [[Johns Hopkins University]] in 1893.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdV_JV1fbZMC&pg=PA215&dq=hockey+baltimore&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=hockey%20baltimore&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Ethnicity and Sports in the United States|first1=George B.|last1=Kirsch|first2=Othello|last2=Harris|first3=Claire Elaine|last3=Nolte|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894, the first artificial ice rink was built in [[Maryland]]. The rink was called the [[North Avenue Ice Palace]], which was located in Baltimore, Maryland. A few years later, in 1896, the first ice hockey league in the United States was formed called The U.S. Amateur Hockey League. It was founded in New York City around the same time as the second artificial ice rink was opened in New York, New York, called the [[St. Nicholas Rink|St. Nicholas Arena]]. The U.S. Amateur Hockey League then became a member of the [[International Ice Hockey Federation]] in 1904. There were five teams from the United States and Ontario that formed the International Ice Hockey Federation. This league only lasted three seasons but it was the first professional ice hockey league that the United States participated in.{{fact|date=March 2018}}\n\nMeanwhile, teams in western Canada formed the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]] in 1911. This league created new designs and rules that helped ice hockey evolve into the game it is today. Some of these new innovations that were created were blue lines that were painted under the ice which divided the ice into three sections, goaltenders are allowed to fall and slide on the ice to help prevent the other team from scoring a goal, forward passing is permitted in the neutral zone, and the game was split into three periods of 20 minutes. In 1912, the game changed again reducing the number of on-ice players to six players from the previous seven.{{fact|date=March 2018}}\n\n==National Hockey League==\n{{Main article|History of the National Hockey League}}\nThe [[National Hockey League|NHL]] is the major professional hockey league in North America, with 24 U.S.-based teams and 7 Canadian-based teams competing for the [[Stanley Cup]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=n3Xn7jMx1RYC&pg=PA912 |title=The American Midwest: An Interpretive Encyclopedia |editor1-first=Andrew R. L. |editor1-last=Cayton |editor2-first=Richard |editor2-last=Sisson |editor3-first=Chris |editor3-last=Zache |page=912 |publisher=Indiana University Press |year=2007 |isbn=978-0-253-34886-9 |accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref> While NHL stars are still not as readily familiar to the general American public as are stars of the NFL, MLB, and the NBA, average attendance for NHL games in the U.S. has surpassed average NBA attendance in recent seasons,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://detroit.cbslocal.com/2014/01/09/why-is-hockey-more-popular-than-basketball-in-detroit-and-across-the-country/ |title=Why Is Hockey More Popular Than Basketball \u2013 In Detroit And Across The Country? |first=Ashley|last=Dunkak|date=9 January 2014|work=CBS Detroit|accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Ryan|last=Glasspiegel |url=https://www.si.com/extra-mustard/2014/01/08/nhl-versus-nba-attendance |title=The NHL is Reportedly Selling Out More Markets Than the NBA This Season |work=Sports Illustrated |date=8 January 2014 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref> buoyed in part by the [[NHL Winter Classic]] being played in large outdoor stadiums.<ref>{{cite news|last=Berr |first=Jonathan |url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/how-the-nhl-got-on-a-winning-streak/ |title=How the NHL got on a scoring streak |work=[[CBS News]] |date=10 November 2014 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.hookedonhockeymagazine.com/hockey-continues-to-grow-in-the-united-states/ |title=Hockey Continues to Grow in the United States |journal=Hooked on Hockey Magazine |first=Igor |last=Burdetskiy |date=21 September 2015 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|first=Jason|last=Brough |url=https://theprovince.com/sports/hockey/nhl-popularity-rising-heres-the-proof |title=NHL Popularity Rising \u2013 Here's the Proof |website=The Province |date=22 April 2008 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1924, the [[Boston Bruins]] were the first American team to join the [[National Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qqy8U_d1LEcC&pg=PA29&dq=boston+bruins+original+six&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiGxaOr_vPQAhWIKsAKHcTVBeMQ6AEIXDAG#v=onepage&q=boston%20bruins%20original%20six&f=false |title=The Legendary Game - Ultimate Hockey Trivia |author=Tom King |page=29 |website=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref> During that season, the first NHL game was played in the United States where the Boston Bruins defeated the [[Montreal Maroons]] 2-1. That same season, the NHL increased the season schedule from 24 games to 30 games.  Three more American teams the [[New York Rangers]], [[Chicago Blackhawks|Chicago Black Hawks]] and [[Detroit Cougars (NHL)|Detroit Cougars]], joined the NHL in the year 1926. That same year, the [[Western Canada Hockey League|Western Hockey League]] fell apart and sold most of its players to the new NHL teams. This makes the NHL the top hockey league in North America. In 1942, the [[Brooklyn Americans]] withdrew from the NHL. This left the Canadiens, Maple Leafs, Red Wings, Bruins, Rangers, and Black Hawks as the only teams left in the NHL for the next 25 years. Those six teams are now called \"[[the Original Six]].\"\n\n[[New Brunswick]]-born skater [[Willie O'Ree]] became the [[Black players in ice hockey|first black ice hockey player in the NHL]] for the [[Boston Bruins]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Harry|last=Thompson |url=http://www.usahockeymagazine.com/article/2013-11/equal-ice-diversity-hockey |title=Equal Ice: Diversity in Hockey |journal=USA Hockey Magazine |date=November 2013 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref> while [[Val James]] was the first African American player to compete in the NHL for the [[Buffalo Sabres]] and [[Toronto Maple Leafs]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/02/04/sports/hockey/val-james-first-us-born-black-player-in-nhl-publishes-autobiography.html|title=N.H.L. Trailblazer Finds Forgiveness in the Tip of a Pen|first=Pat|last=Borzi|date=3 February 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-10-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1972 the [[World Hockey Association]] formed of 12 teams from Canada and the United States intended to rival the NHL but ultimately failed and many of the teams merged with the NHL.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VUT0v_BSkFoC&pg=PA2&dq=world+hockey+association&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiTm8fH_vPQAhUJM8AKHTICBPEQ6AEIMjAB#v=onepage&q=world%20hockey%20association&f=false |title=The Complete Historical and Statistical Reference to the World Hockey ... |author=Scott Surgent |page=2 |website=Books.google.co.uk |date= |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref>\n\n==Stanley Cup==\nThe [[Stanley Cup]] is the oldest trophy in North American sports. [[Lord Stanley of Preston]] was appointed by [[Queen Victoria]] to be the Governor General of Canada on June 11, 1888. While governor, Ice hockey was still just forming in Canada. He first got to see the game of hockey played at Montreal's 1889 Winter Carnival. During the carnival he watched the Montreal Victorias play the Montreal Hockey Club. Since then he and his family became very involved in the game of ice hockey. His two sons, Arthur and Algernon, convinced their father to donate a trophy that would be considered to be a visible sign of the ice hockey championship. This trophy was a silver bowl inlaid with gold.  The trophy was first presented in 1893 and was called the Dominion Hockey Challenge Cup. The name of the trophy was later changed to the famous name, The Stanley Cup.\n\nIn 1914 the [[Portland Rosebuds (ice hockey)|Portland Rosebuds]], an American-based team, joined the [[Pacific Coast Hockey Association]]. After that, the trustees of the Stanley Cup made a statement that the Stanley Cup was no longer for the best team in Canada, but now the best team in the whole world. The Rosebuds became the first American team to compete in the Stanley Cup Finals two years later. In the year 1917, the team [[Seattle Metropolitans]] was the first American team to win the Stanley Cup.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattletimes.com/sports/other-sports/when-seattle-was-hockeytown-usa/|title=When Seattle was Hockeytown USA|date=2 March 2013|publisher=SB Nation|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref> Once that season was over, the National Hockey Association was changed into the NHL or the [[National Hockey League]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sbnation.com/2014/8/5/5969737/seattle-metropolitans-history-stanley-cup-hockey-pcha-nhl|title=Remembering America's first Stanley Cup champion|first=Adam|last=Gretz|date=5 August 2014|publisher=[[Seattle Times]]|accessdate=17 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Minor leagues==\n\nMinor league professional hockey leagues in the U.S. include the [[American Hockey League]] and the [[ECHL]]. Additionally, nine U.S.-based teams compete in the three member leagues of the [[Canadian Hockey League]].\n[[USA Hockey]] is the official governing body for amateur hockey in the U.S. The [[United States Hockey Hall of Fame]] is located in [[Eveleth, Minnesota]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=f9YJSX7JQAoC&pg=PA119&lpg=PA119&dq=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&source=bl&ots=jTPF_giLq1&sig=DekDXtoFh7dB1QWTLBM3oTcPHus&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiFxa_HhvDQAhXNFsAKHXAOBYY4MhDoAQggMAE#v=onepage&q=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&f=false|title=Boating Life|publisher=|accessdate=13 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vYhlFmPSNgEC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&source=bl&ots=JZVC6ur2lr&sig=yBc6bFHVblRJj-_uhapGOXdxxCA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiK1uDjhvDQAhVFJcAKHfHCDWU4HhDoAQgeMAE#v=onepage&q=United%20States%20Hockey%20Hall%20of%20Fame%20%20Eveleth,%20Minnesota&f=false|title=Hockey in Providence|first=Jim|last=Mancuso|date=1 January 2006|publisher=Arcadia Publishing|accessdate=13 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\n==Ice hockey structure==\n\n{{Main article|United States ice hockey structure}}\n\nThe '''United States ice hockey structure''' includes elements from traditional American scholastic [[high school]] and [[college]] athletics, affiliated and independent [[minor league]]s, and the unique \"[[Junior ice hockey#Major junior|Major Junior]]\" leagues. The [[hierarchy]] of the ice hockey league system forms a pyramid with a large number of regional minor and development leagues making up the base of the pyramid and a linear progression through the professional minor leagues leading to the Nation Hockey League at the top of the pyramid.\n\n==Amateur ice hockey==\n[[College ice hockey|College hockey]] has a regional following in the northeastern and upper midwestern United States. It is increasingly being used to develop players for the NHL and other professional leagues (the U.S. has junior leagues, the [[United States Hockey League]] and [[North American Hockey League]], but they are more restricted to protect junior players' college eligibility). The [[Frozen Four]] is college hockey's national championship.\n\nSummer [[senior ice hockey]] is increasing in popularity in the 21st century, with [[Edina, Minnesota]]'s Da Beauty League and [[Buffalo, New York]]'s Fattey Hockey League both drawing NHL players who use the leagues to stay in shape during the offseason.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/466460/2018/08/09/heres-how-dahlin-mittelstadt-ended-up-playing-buffalo-summer-league-hockey/|first=Joe|last=Yerdon|title=Here\u2019s how Dahlin, Mittelstadt ended up playing in Buffalo\u2019s Fattey Hockey League|work=[[The Athletic]]|date=August 10, 2018|accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref> Da Beauty League, established in 2016, is considered the nation's premier summer ice hockey league and benefits from corporate sponsorship from the Minnesota business community.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/nhl/2018/07/12/da-beauty-league-nick-bjugstad-brock-boeser-summer-hockey|title=NHLer-Laden Da Beauty League Returns for Third Season of Summer Hockey\n|first=Michael|last=Blinn|work=[[SI.com]]|date=July 12, 2018|accessdate=August 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Olympics==\n{{main article|Ice hockey at the Olympic Games}}\n[[Image:1936 US Olympic Ice Hockey Team.jpg|right|thumb|The bronze medal winning [[United States at the 1936 Winter Olympics|1936 American Olympic team]].]]\nA hockey tournament debuted in the Summer Olympics in 1920 and would later also be recognized as the first World Ice Hockey Championship. Canada took the gold medal, with the United States getting the silver. The Canadians went on to claim three consecutive golds after the sport was permanently transferred to the newly established Winter Olympics in 1924. In 1936, their streak was ended by the British team that went on to beat the Canadians and tie the Americans, claiming the gold. Canada reclaimed gold in 1948 and defended it in 1952. However, the Soviet Union ended Canadian dominance in 1956, winning gold, and went on to win all Olympic tournaments until 1992 with 1960 and 1980, when the Americans were victorious, being lone exceptions. Much of this has to do with the fact that, unlike the Soviets, the Canadians were unable to use their best players. After 1992, four nations won gold medals: Canada (7th, 8th, and 9th titles), Sweden (1st and 2nd title), Czech Republic (1st title), and, the most recent champions, Russia (9th title). From 1998 to 2014, NHL players participated in the Olympics. In 1994 and 2018, players from all professional leagues except the NHL and AHL competed. Prior to 1947 there was no nationally recognized national governing body for ice hockey in the United States. The Amateur Hockey Association of the United States or AHAUS, which later became [[USA Hockey]], was created that year and has remained the governing body of ice hockey in the United States since then. The [[United States men's national ice hockey team|United States men's team]] has won two gold medals ([[Ice hockey at the 1960 Winter Olympics|1960]], [[Ice hockey at the 1980 Winter Olympics|1980]]), eight silver medals ([[Ice hockey at the 1920 Winter Olympics|1920]], [[Ice hockey at the 1924 Winter Olympics|1924]], [[Ice hockey at the 1932 Winter Olympics|1932]], [[Ice hockey at the 1952 Winter Olympics|1952]], [[Ice hockey at the 1956 Winter Olympics|1956]], [[Ice hockey at the 1972 Winter Olympics|1972]], [[Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics|2002]], [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics|2010]]) and one bronze medal ([[Ice hockey at the 1936 Winter Olympics|1936]]). The 1980 gold medal victory is still remembered as one of the greatest upsets in sporting history, with team USA beating four-time defending champions the USSR in the medal round. The [[United States women's national ice hockey team|women's team]] has won two gold medals ([[Ice hockey at the 1998 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|1998]], [[Ice hockey at the 2018 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2018]]), three silver medals ([[Ice hockey at the 2002 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2002]], [[Ice hockey at the 2010 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2010]], [[Ice hockey at the 2014 Winter Olympics|2014]]), and one bronze medal ([[Ice hockey at the 2006 Winter Olympics \u2013 Women's tournament|2006]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xdV_JV1fbZMC&pg=PA219&lpg=PA219&dq=Race%20and%20Ethnicity%20in%20the%20NHL&source=bl&ots=fiJmB3dwQJ&sig=LYuNSG2GvZD-I06xrvl7-0v8LUY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH_76T_PLQAhUMLcAKHQM6Cys4ChDoAQgmMAI#v=snippet&q=ahaus&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Ethnicity and Sports in the United States|first1=George B.|last1=Kirsch|first2=Othello|last2=Harris|first3=Claire Elaine|last3=Nolte|date=1 January 2000|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|accessdate=14 December 2016|via=Google Books}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/olympics/story/_/id/12360850/miracle-ice-1980-us-olympic-hockey-team-reunites-lake-placid|title=All living 'Miracle' members reunite|publisher=[[ESPN]]|date=22 February 2015|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/hockey/u-s-shocks-russians-4-3-article-1.2014732|title=Miracle on Ice! Mike Eruzione's goal, Jim Craig's heroics lead U.S. to stunning upset over the Russians in Lake Placid, 4\u20133|first=Lawrie|last=Mifflin|date=23 February 1980|work= New York Daily News|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"cbssports1980\">{{cite news|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/news/american-hockey-has-come-a-long-way-since-1980s-miraculous-gold/|title=American hockey has come a long way since 1980's miraculous gold|first=Chris|last=Peters|date=24 February 2015|work=CBS Sports|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/longterm/olympics1998/history/memories/80-hock.htm|title=U.S. Shocks Soviets in Ice Hockey, 4\u20133|publisher=Washington Post|first=Leonard|last=Shapiro|date=23 February 1980|work=[[The Washington Post]]|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/big/0222.html |title=U.S. Defeats Soviet Squad In Olympic Hockey by 4\u20133 |first=Gerald|last=Eskenazi|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=23 February 1980 |accessdate=2016-09-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/nhl/story/_/id/9418183/usa-hockey-encourages-kids-nhl-dreams-play-other-sports-espn-magazine|title=Miracle on ice|first=Tom|last=Farrey|date=26 June 2013|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.si.com/nhl/2015/02/23/1980-usa-olympic-hockey-team-miracle-on-ice-35th-reunion-at-lake-placid|title=Poignant reunion for the Miracle on Ice team at Lake Placid|first=Stefanie|last=Gordon|date=23 February 2015|work=Sports Illustrated|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Women's ice hockey==\n{{main article|History of women's ice hockey in the United States}}\nWomen's ice hockey is less popular.<ref>{{cite news|first=Seth|last=Berkman |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/03/05/sports/hockey/obstacles-for-global-talent-in-national-womens-hockey-league.html |title=Obstacles for Global Talent in National Women's Hockey League |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=4 March 2016 |accessdate=2016-10-09}}</ref> The [[National Women's Hockey League]], founded in 2015, is the first in the country to pay its players, and featured four teams from the Northeast.<ref>{{cite news|author= |url=https://www.npr.org/2016/01/21/463073576/womens-hockey-takes-stage-as-new-pro-sports-league |title=Women's Hockey Takes Stage As New Pro Sports League |work=[[NPR]] |date=21 January 2016 |accessdate=2016-10-09}}</ref> Through partnerships with NHL teams, the league survived and expanded to five teams for its fourth season in 2018, adding the [[Minnesota Whitecaps]] (a long-established independent team) that year. Four of the league's five teams are owned and operated by the league itself; the lone exception is the Whitecaps. In 2019, a player strike led to two of the NHL partnerships being severed and one of the teams, the [[Buffalo Beauts]], being placed into legal limbo after [[Pegula Sports and Entertainment]] (which had purchased the team in 2017) surrendered the NWHL franchise back to the league but not the intellectual property or arena lease. The player strike was brought on by a disconnect between the demands of the NWHL's players to be paid and treated more professionally than they have been, and the NWHL's inability to enter into the agreements necessary for those demands to be met.\n\n==Television coverage==\n{{main article|History of the National Hockey League on United States television}}\n{{Expand section|date=October 2016}}\n\nIn 1957, [[NHL on CBS|CBS]] was the first U.S. television network to carry NHL games.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1957/10/28/605545/the-hockey-rebellion\n|title=The Hockey Rebellion|date=October 28, 1957|first=Dan|last=Parker|journal=Sports Illustrated}}</ref> Later, the television network NBC also started carrying some NHL games. Both television networks held rights to show NHL games at times, but neither television network showed a full NHL schedule. They only carried select games from the Stanley Cup Finals. From the year 1971 to the year 1995 no United States television network had exclusive coverage of the NHL games. The USA television network started carrying 35 regular-season games and played the full schedule of the playoff games from the year 1981 to 1985.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.si.com/vault/1983/01/24/625121/getting-down-to-business |title=Getting Down To Business |date=January 24, 1983 |first=William |last=Taaffe |journal=Sports Illustrated |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150427143048/http://www.si.com/vault/1983/01/24/625121/getting-down-to-business |archivedate=April 27, 2015 }}</ref> [[ESPN National Hockey Night|ESPN]] replaced the USA network in 1985 and then [[SportsChannel America|\nSports Channel]] replaced ESPN in 1989. ESPN came back and later took over the National Hockey Contract in 1993. The [[NHL on Fox|Fox network]] joined ESPN in the year 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-09-10/sports/sp-36827_1_cable-contract |title=NHL Agrees on $155-Million Deal With Fox - latimes |website=Articles.latimes.com |date=1994-09-10 |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Sandomir |first=Richard |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1994/09/10/sports/hockey-fox-outbids-cbs-for-nhl-games.html |title=HOCKEY - Fox Outbids CBS for N.H.L. Games |website=NYTimes.com |date=1994-09-10 |accessdate=2016-12-14}}</ref> NBC and sister network [[NBCSN]] have held exclusive national rights to the NHL since 2005.\n\n==Pop culture==\n{{main article|Ice hockey in popular culture}}\n{{Expand section|date=October 2016}}\nMovies such as ''[[Miracle (2004 film)|Miracle]]'', ''[[The Mighty Ducks]]'', ''[[Youngblood (1986 film)|Youngblood]]'', and ''[[Soul on Ice (film)|Soul on Ice]]'' have become part of American culture regarding hockey.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://time.com/mighty-ducks/ |title=Quack, Quack, Quack: An Oral History of the ''Mighty Ducks'' Trilogy |first=Eric|last=Dodds|journal=Time |date=9 June 2014 |accessdate=2016-10-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=mWCkYfx6ydA |title=Top 10 Hockey Movies |publisher=[[Watchmojo]] |date=8 June 2015 |accessdate=2016-10-21}}</ref>\n\n==Fanbase==\n\nTraditionally, ice hockey has been played predominantly by [[White American|Caucasians]] in the United States and attended by white Americans and the [[Sports fan|fans]] are the most affluent of the 4 major team sports watched in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://psmag.com/why-the-ice-is-white-4afcd6bfd47a#.o7h8jhtjg |title=Why the Ice Is White |first=Wes |last=Judd| website=[[Pacific Standard]] |date=19 June 2015 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/christinasettimi/2015/11/24/the-nhls-least-engaged-fans/|title=The NHL's Least Engaged Fans|first=Christina|last=Settimi|date=24 November 2015|website=Forbes|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/business/archive/2014/02/which-sports-have-the-whitest-richest-oldest-fans/283626/|title=Which Sports Have the Whitest/Richest/Oldest Fans?|first=Derek|last=Thompson|date=10 February 2014|journal=The Atlantic|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/blogs/nhl-puck-daddy/nhl-least-diverse-most-advertiser-friendly-tv-audience-194010102--nhl.html|title=NHL has least diverse, but most advertiser friendly, TV audience|first=Greg|last=Wyshynski|date=27 January 2014|website=Puck Daddy (Yahoo Sport)|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIce hockey is traditionally popular in [[Sports in Massachusetts|Massachusetts]], [[Sports in Michigan|Michigan]], and [[Sports in Minnesota|Minnesota]] within the United States. Minnesota is known as the hockey capital of the USA.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://slapshot.blogs.nytimes.com/2011/02/20/where-hockey-is-growing-state-by-state/|title=Where Hockey is Growing, State by State|first=Jeff Z.|last=Klein|date=20 February 2011|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/643555-the-state-of-hockey-ranking-the-top-10-hockey-states-in-america|title=The State of Hockey: Ranking the Top 10 Hockey States in America|first=Erik|last=Johnson|website=Bleacher Report|date=23 March 2011|accessdate=23 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"nytimes1\"/><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/sports/nhl-looks-to-fix-diversity-issues-w454345|title=NHL Looks to Inner-Cities for New Generation of Diverse Players|publisher=Rolling Stone|accessdate=9 December 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe [[NHL]] is trying to grow the sport of ice hockey by attempting to diversify the fanbase and expand from its [[Race and ethnicity in the NHL|traditional demographic]].<ref name=\"auto\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2015/04/13/399292644/nhl-aims-to-include-more-minority-players-to-expand-fan-base|title=NHL Aims To Include More Minority Players To Expand Fan Base|publisher=NPR|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/blog/onenacion/post/_/id/3769/hockey-eyes-hispanic-fans-for-growth |title=Hockey eyes Hispanic fans for growth |first=Martin|last=Bater|website=ESPN |date=1 May 2016|accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Yates |first=Clinton |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/im-a-black-hockey-fan-we-do-exist/2012/02/27/gIQAa7MHnR_story.html |title=I'm a black hockey fan. We do exist. |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=2 March 2012 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref> A notable example is the [[Chicago Blackhawks]] has seen a significant increase in attention from ethnic minorites groups since their [[Stanley cup]] successes in the 2010s, which has resulted in the team setting up outreach programs for urban youths and low income neighbourhoods.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/hockey/blackhawks/ct-blackhawks-fans-african-americans-spt-0612-20150611-story.html |title=African-American fans have the highest growth rate among NHL fans |first=Shannon |last=Ryan |date=11 June 2015 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/chicago/nhl/story/_/id/11707540/how-chicago-chicago-blackhawks-trying-diversify-youth-hockey |title=How Chicago, Chicago Blackhawks are trying to diversify youth hockey |website=Espn.com |date=2014-10-21 |accessdate=2016-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title= Hockey interest among minorities gaining speed, NHL says|publisher= Chicago Tribune|date=|url= http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2013-06-17/news/ct-met-hockey-minorities-20130617_1_blackhawks-ray-emery-nhl-team|accessdate=2016-10-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.co.uk/nhl/story/_/id/13093287/chicago-blackhawks-see-increase-minority-hockey-fans |title=Chicago Blackhawks see increase in minority hockey fans |first=Scott|last=Powers|publisher=ESPN |date=19 June 2015 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref> The [[Washington Capitals]] also have noteworthy outreach programs for to garner interest ice hockey.<ref>{{cite news|last=El |first=Tarik |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/capitals/alex-ovechkin-has-made-ice-cool-for-areas-youth-athletes/2012/02/02/gIQASj9OzQ_story.html |title=Capitals' Alex Ovechkin has made ice hockey cool for Washington area's youth athletes |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=8 February 2012 |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://cnsmaryland.org/2015/05/14/hockey-growing-in-maryland-as-washington-capitals-ovechkin-make-waves-in-nhl/ |title=Hockey Growing in Maryland as Washington Capitals, Ovechkin Make Waves In NHL|first=Brian|last=Marron|date=14 May 2015|work=Capital News Service |accessdate=2016-09-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/309167-hockey-in-the-hood-but-is-the-hood-in-hockey|title=\"Hockey in The Hood\": But Is The Hood in Hockey?|first=Angie|last=Lewis|publisher=Bleacher Report|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe NHL has outreach programs like \"Hockey is for Everyone\" to make ice hockey more accessible to urban youth and low income communities.<ref>{{cite news|last=Reid |first=Jason |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/capitals/nhl-diversity-an-idea-that-needs-to-be-heard/2011/09/30/gIQAp2wARL_story.html |title=NHL diversity: An idea that needs to be heard  |work=[[The Washington Post]] |date=6 October 2011 |accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2005/11/13/sports/hockey/the-nhls-diversity-program-is-beginning-to-pay-dividends.html?_r=0|title=The NHL's Diversity Program is Beginning to Pay Dividends|first=Jason|last=Diamosnov|date=13 November 2005|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=2016-10-17}}</ref>\n\n==Present day==\nAs of the year 2015, there are over 2,000 ice rinks in the United States alone (United States, 2008). Also, the NHL still exists and there are now 31 teams participating in the league, with 24 in the United States and 7 in [[Canada]].  As of spring 2014, United States has won 16 medals (gold, silver, and bronze) total.\n\nThe U.S. now has more youth hockey players than all other countries, excluding Canada, combined.<ref name=Dryden>{{cite web|url=http://grantland.com/features/miracle-off-ice/ |title=Miracle Off Ice |first=Ken |last=Dryden |authorlink=Ken Dryden |work=[[Grantland|Grantland.com]] |date=February 20, 2014 |accessdate=February 20, 2014}}</ref> The legacy of the Miracle on Ice is believed to be influential in popularizing the sport from a fringe sport to a mainstream sport.<ref name=\"cbssports1980\"/>\n\n==Number of registered players by state==\nNumber of registered hockey players, including male, female and junior, provided by [[USA Hockey]], as of October 2019. <ref>{{cite web |title=2018-19 Final Registration Report |url=https://cdn1.sportngin.com/attachments/document/2210-1687681/2018-19_Final_Registration_Report.pdf |publisher=[[USA Hockey]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=US States - Ranked by Population 2019 |url=http://worldpopulationreview.com/states/ |publisher=[[World Population Review]] |accessdate=October 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Country\n!Players\n!% of pop